00:00:25.950 --> 00:00:28.010
PETER CARR: So, I welcome
comments or questions

00:00:28.010 --> 00:00:29.480
at any point during this talk.

00:00:29.480 --> 00:00:31.730
We have an hour and a half,
and I have only 50 slides.

00:00:31.730 --> 00:00:33.630
So we should be OK.

00:00:33.630 --> 00:00:38.000
So, this is joint
work with Jiming Yu,

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:41.360
who's a colleague of mine in
my group at Morgan Stanley.

00:00:41.360 --> 00:00:42.900
I head up the global
market modeling

00:00:42.900 --> 00:00:43.930
team at Morgan Stanley.

00:00:43.930 --> 00:00:47.510
It's a group of about 70
PhDs, mostly, spread around

00:00:47.510 --> 00:00:49.140
the world.

00:00:49.140 --> 00:00:52.690
There's about 30
of us in New York,

00:00:52.690 --> 00:00:57.540
some in London, quite a few
Budapest, and a few in Beijing.

00:00:57.540 --> 00:01:00.370
The title of this talk
is Can We Recover?

00:01:00.370 --> 00:01:04.970
And it's meant as
a triple entendre.

00:01:04.970 --> 00:01:09.020
So, it could refer to either
the systemic risk arising

00:01:09.020 --> 00:01:14.740
from the credit crisis, or the
main result in a recent paper

00:01:14.740 --> 00:01:18.880
by a professor here at MIT named
Steve Ross in the Sloan School,

00:01:18.880 --> 00:01:23.210
or it could actually be the
academic and practitioner

00:01:23.210 --> 00:01:27.910
reaction to this
result. So, it's really

00:01:27.910 --> 00:01:30.520
about two and three.

00:01:30.520 --> 00:01:33.765
So, it's not about can we
recover from the crisis.

00:01:38.750 --> 00:01:41.160
There's a professor at Sloan
School named Stephen Ross.

00:01:41.160 --> 00:01:46.870
And he's very well-known
in academic finance.

00:01:46.870 --> 00:01:49.060
Your professor was kind
enough to mention that I won

00:01:49.060 --> 00:01:50.380
Financial Engineer of the Year.

00:01:50.380 --> 00:01:53.510
And that was two years ago.

00:01:53.510 --> 00:01:55.140
I was like the 20th winner.

00:01:55.140 --> 00:01:56.740
He was the second winner.

00:02:01.420 --> 00:02:05.550
The first winner was another
MIT professor, Bob Merton.

00:02:05.550 --> 00:02:12.030
So anyway, he wrote a
paper a couple years ago,

00:02:12.030 --> 00:02:15.300
and it's only now
about to be published.

00:02:15.300 --> 00:02:17.360
So this is like typical
in academic circles.

00:02:17.360 --> 00:02:22.290
It takes a long time
for a paper to come out.

00:02:22.290 --> 00:02:25.440
And this paper is coming
out in Journal of Finance.

00:02:25.440 --> 00:02:27.040
That's what JF stands for.

00:02:27.040 --> 00:02:30.530
And Journal of Finance
is the main journal

00:02:30.530 --> 00:02:34.060
for the academic
finance community.

00:02:34.060 --> 00:02:38.120
And the title of the paper
is The Recovery Theorem.

00:02:38.120 --> 00:02:42.480
And that's also the title of
the theorem one in his paper.

00:02:42.480 --> 00:02:44.810
And that theorem
one we'll go over.

00:02:44.810 --> 00:02:49.360
And it gives a sufficient set
of conditions under which,

00:02:49.360 --> 00:02:53.930
what Professor Ross calls
"natural probabilities,"

00:02:53.930 --> 00:02:56.780
at a point in time
can be determined

00:02:56.780 --> 00:03:00.905
from-- OK mathematically,
from exact knowledge

00:03:00.905 --> 00:03:03.030
of Arrow-Debreu security
prices, which you probably

00:03:03.030 --> 00:03:04.071
don't know what they are.

00:03:04.071 --> 00:03:06.990
But less mathematically,
we'll just

00:03:06.990 --> 00:03:10.580
say from market
prices of derivatives.

00:03:10.580 --> 00:03:12.190
OK, so derivatives
you've heard of,

00:03:12.190 --> 00:03:16.770
I'm sure-- things like options,
for example, on stocks or stock

00:03:16.770 --> 00:03:20.340
indices, could be on currencies.

00:03:20.340 --> 00:03:22.760
So, imagine that you
look at Bloomberg.

00:03:22.760 --> 00:03:25.600
Bloomberg publishes a
whole bunch of prices.

00:03:25.600 --> 00:03:31.480
And the idea is that you
take this information,

00:03:31.480 --> 00:03:35.290
and from it you're learning
what the market believes

00:03:35.290 --> 00:03:38.610
are the probabilities
concerning the future.

00:03:38.610 --> 00:03:43.960
And so, if the option is
on S&amp;P 500 stock index,

00:03:43.960 --> 00:03:47.350
then you're learning
from options prices what

00:03:47.350 --> 00:03:49.950
the market believes
are the likelihoods

00:03:49.950 --> 00:04:03.810
of various possible
levels for the S&amp;P 500.

00:04:03.810 --> 00:04:09.460
So, we take this information on
Bloomberg and, truth be told,

00:04:09.460 --> 00:04:11.710
we use it along with
some assumptions

00:04:11.710 --> 00:04:17.720
to extract these implied
market probabilities.

00:04:17.720 --> 00:04:20.510
So, I want to tell you
what those assumptions are.

00:04:20.510 --> 00:04:26.160
And so, the actual
output of this analysis

00:04:26.160 --> 00:04:30.390
is a probability
transition matrix.

00:04:30.390 --> 00:04:32.500
Or, if you do it
in continuous time,

00:04:32.500 --> 00:04:35.550
you'd call it a-- in
continuous state space,

00:04:35.550 --> 00:04:40.700
you'd call it a transition
probability density function.

00:04:40.700 --> 00:04:45.370
So the key word there
is "transition."

00:04:45.370 --> 00:04:46.940
And what transition
means is you're

00:04:46.940 --> 00:04:49.840
getting not only the
probabilities going

00:04:49.840 --> 00:04:55.830
from, say, the current S&amp;P level
to any one of several levels,

00:04:55.830 --> 00:04:58.330
but even the
probabilities of going

00:04:58.330 --> 00:05:02.720
from some other level than
we're presently at today

00:05:02.720 --> 00:05:05.287
to that range of levels.

00:05:05.287 --> 00:05:06.870
You could say, for
example, the market

00:05:06.870 --> 00:05:09.320
believes that given
that we're here now

00:05:09.320 --> 00:05:15.700
with S&amp;P at, say, 1,500,
that the probability of more

00:05:15.700 --> 00:05:22.165
than doubling is one
half, for example--

00:05:22.165 --> 00:05:23.290
which would be really high.

00:05:23.290 --> 00:05:28.070
But you know, I'm just
picking numbers randomly here.

00:05:28.070 --> 00:05:33.530
And you can even say that if
S&amp;P were to drop instantaneously

00:05:33.530 --> 00:05:36.240
to half its level, that
the probability of more

00:05:36.240 --> 00:05:40.930
than doubling from there
is, say, one-third.

00:05:40.930 --> 00:05:44.125
So, you can answer
questions like that.

00:05:44.125 --> 00:05:47.140
That's The output of
this type of thinking.

00:05:51.160 --> 00:05:56.320
So there'll be three
probability measures

00:05:56.320 --> 00:05:58.700
that we can be thinking about.

00:05:58.700 --> 00:06:01.160
And we'll call them
P, Q, and R. And I'd

00:06:01.160 --> 00:06:03.510
like to tell you what
each of them means.

00:06:03.510 --> 00:06:06.600
So P stands for physical
probability measures.

00:06:06.600 --> 00:06:08.600
So the P is for physical.

00:06:08.600 --> 00:06:13.490
And think of that as
the actual objective

00:06:13.490 --> 00:06:21.230
reality of future states
for, say, S&amp;P 500.

00:06:21.230 --> 00:06:28.160
So let's say God knows that,
for example, the probability

00:06:28.160 --> 00:06:32.690
that S&amp;P is up by the end
of the year is one half.

00:06:32.690 --> 00:06:37.050
And we, unfortunately, not
being God, don't know that.

00:06:37.050 --> 00:06:39.690
But let's say the
philosophy is that.

00:06:39.690 --> 00:06:42.790
There is some sort of
true probability of S&amp;P

00:06:42.790 --> 00:06:45.350
being up at the end of the year.

00:06:45.350 --> 00:06:49.840
And let's say I used a half.

00:06:49.840 --> 00:06:51.960
Maybe it's 60%.

00:06:51.960 --> 00:06:53.690
If it is 60%, then
the probability

00:06:53.690 --> 00:06:57.190
of S&amp;P being down at the
end of the year is 40%.

00:06:57.190 --> 00:07:07.430
And the point is P
is meant to indicate

00:07:07.430 --> 00:07:11.200
the frequencies with which
S&amp;P 500 in my example

00:07:11.200 --> 00:07:14.230
takes on various values.

00:07:14.230 --> 00:07:16.730
Now, there's another
probability measure

00:07:16.730 --> 00:07:19.770
that people in derivatives spend
a lot of time working with.

00:07:19.770 --> 00:07:22.490
And that's called risk-neutral
probability measure,

00:07:22.490 --> 00:07:25.020
and it's often
denoted by a letter Q.

00:07:25.020 --> 00:07:29.149
So we'll denote it
by Q. And the concept

00:07:29.149 --> 00:07:30.690
of a risk-neutral
probability measure

00:07:30.690 --> 00:07:35.670
was also actually proposed
by Steve Ross many years ago.

00:07:35.670 --> 00:07:47.540
And it's called risk
neutral because when you're

00:07:47.540 --> 00:07:53.720
working with it, if you
think about how fast prices

00:07:53.720 --> 00:07:58.480
appreciate over time,
then they grow randomly.

00:07:58.480 --> 00:08:02.330
But on average, under this
risk-neutral measure Q,

00:08:02.330 --> 00:08:05.250
the grow at the same rate as
your bank balance would grow.

00:08:08.130 --> 00:08:11.150
So your bank balance,
let's say, nowadays

00:08:11.150 --> 00:08:14.100
is growing at best
at the rate of 1%.

00:08:14.100 --> 00:08:20.760
And when you look at how
fast, historically, stocks

00:08:20.760 --> 00:08:26.060
have grown, it's actually much
higher, on average, than 1%.

00:08:26.060 --> 00:08:28.020
It's more like about 9%.

00:08:28.020 --> 00:08:33.669
So we would call the
difference between 9% and 1%--

00:08:33.669 --> 00:08:37.559
we call that 8%
differential risk premium.

00:08:37.559 --> 00:08:42.434
And let me just pretend
there's no dividends

00:08:42.434 --> 00:08:46.080
to keep life simple
when I say this.

00:08:46.080 --> 00:08:52.470
So now, this
risk-neutral measure

00:08:52.470 --> 00:08:54.744
is kind of a
fictitious probability

00:08:54.744 --> 00:08:56.160
measure in the
sense that it's not

00:08:56.160 --> 00:08:59.890
describing the actual
probabilities or frequencies

00:08:59.890 --> 00:09:04.140
of transitions, it's
more a device, or a tool,

00:09:04.140 --> 00:09:07.930
or a trick that's handy.

00:09:07.930 --> 00:09:10.800
And one of its properties that
causes it to earn the name

00:09:10.800 --> 00:09:15.770
risk-neutral probability measure
is that when you look at how

00:09:15.770 --> 00:09:20.680
fast, say, S&amp;P grows on
average under this risk-neutral

00:09:20.680 --> 00:09:25.460
probability measure Q, it would
be growing nowadays at 1%--

00:09:25.460 --> 00:09:31.050
so the same as your bank
balance is growing at.

00:09:31.050 --> 00:09:33.860
So the word
risk-neutral is meant

00:09:33.860 --> 00:09:37.510
to indicate that the growth
rate under this measure

00:09:37.510 --> 00:09:43.920
is consistent with investors in
the economy being risk-neutral,

00:09:43.920 --> 00:09:46.500
meaning that they require
no premium for bearing risk.

00:09:52.490 --> 00:09:54.910
Now there's a third
probability measure

00:09:54.910 --> 00:09:58.360
that we're going to be talking
about today that actually you

00:09:58.360 --> 00:10:00.860
won't find any literature on.

00:10:00.860 --> 00:10:05.150
And we're going to call it R.
It seems like a natural letter

00:10:05.150 --> 00:10:08.280
to pick, having already
gone through P and Q.

00:10:08.280 --> 00:10:14.550
And you can think
of the R as standing

00:10:14.550 --> 00:10:17.417
for recovered
probability measure.

00:10:17.417 --> 00:10:19.250
And it's going to be
the probability measure

00:10:19.250 --> 00:10:23.710
that we get from market prices
as I was talking about earlier.

00:10:23.710 --> 00:10:31.690
And the operational
meaning of this R measure

00:10:31.690 --> 00:10:36.110
is it's capturing the market's
beliefs regarding the future.

00:10:36.110 --> 00:10:40.530
But we allow for the possibility
that the market could be wrong.

00:10:40.530 --> 00:10:43.980
So we're applying this
to say houses and housing

00:10:43.980 --> 00:10:48.180
prices in, say,
2005-- it may well

00:10:48.180 --> 00:10:50.160
be that if we
looked at Bloomberg

00:10:50.160 --> 00:10:54.280
and got prices of
mortgage-backed securities,

00:10:54.280 --> 00:10:58.430
that we would extract an
R probability measure that

00:10:58.430 --> 00:11:01.990
says housing prices
are going to continue

00:11:01.990 --> 00:11:05.310
on their incessant
upward trajectory.

00:11:05.310 --> 00:11:06.950
And, you know,
we're going to keep

00:11:06.950 --> 00:11:10.520
growing at the rate
of, say, 15% a year

00:11:10.520 --> 00:11:13.450
each year for the next 10
years, or something like that.

00:11:13.450 --> 00:11:17.650
So, that could be what the
market's beliefs were back

00:11:17.650 --> 00:11:19.390
in 2005.

00:11:19.390 --> 00:11:21.520
And we know now that
those beliefs were wrong,

00:11:21.520 --> 00:11:24.580
if that was what the
market was inferring.

00:11:24.580 --> 00:11:28.150
So, I want to allow for at least
the theoretical possibility

00:11:28.150 --> 00:11:30.290
that the market could be wrong.

00:11:30.290 --> 00:11:32.530
And so, that's why I'm
drawing a distinction,

00:11:32.530 --> 00:11:35.140
let's say, between the
R probability measure

00:11:35.140 --> 00:11:37.870
that captures the market's
beliefs and the P probability

00:11:37.870 --> 00:11:41.250
measure that captures
physical reality.

00:11:41.250 --> 00:11:45.040
So now, there's a lot of people
in finance who simply cannot

00:11:45.040 --> 00:11:48.440
accept the possibility that
the market could be wrong.

00:11:48.440 --> 00:11:51.680
And for those people--
the sort of true believers

00:11:51.680 --> 00:11:54.385
in market efficiency--
they are free to set R

00:11:54.385 --> 00:11:57.210
to P every time they
see an R. But I want

00:11:57.210 --> 00:12:00.730
to allow for the possibility
that what we recover

00:12:00.730 --> 00:12:03.600
is not physical probabilities,
but simply the market beliefs.

00:12:11.040 --> 00:12:12.800
And anyway, it's
kind of semantics.

00:12:12.800 --> 00:12:16.250
It's good semantics if the
probability measure we recover

00:12:16.250 --> 00:12:20.350
is the one Ross
said we should get.

00:12:20.350 --> 00:12:21.200
R stands for Ross.

00:12:24.660 --> 00:12:26.400
So Ross calls the
probability measure

00:12:26.400 --> 00:12:29.530
that we recover-- he calls them
natural probability measures.

00:12:29.530 --> 00:12:32.686
And well, let's
say, that suggests

00:12:32.686 --> 00:12:34.060
that the risk-neutral
probability

00:12:34.060 --> 00:12:38.839
measures are unnatural, which
I think is fair actually.

00:12:38.839 --> 00:12:40.630
Because when you hear
the word probability,

00:12:40.630 --> 00:12:42.350
you tend to think
about frequencies

00:12:42.350 --> 00:12:44.112
with which events occur.

00:12:44.112 --> 00:12:45.820
And the risk-neutral
probability measures

00:12:45.820 --> 00:12:49.502
do not give you the frequencies
with which events occur.

00:12:49.502 --> 00:12:51.460
What the risk-neutral
probability measures give

00:12:51.460 --> 00:12:57.530
you is instead prices of
so-called Arrow-Debreu

00:12:57.530 --> 00:12:58.810
securities.

00:12:58.810 --> 00:13:01.530
So, let me give you a
sense of what that means.

00:13:01.530 --> 00:13:06.460
So say I tell you that the
risk-neutral probability of S&amp;P

00:13:06.460 --> 00:13:10.930
500 being up at the
end of the year is 40%.

00:13:13.580 --> 00:13:16.280
Then how should
you interpret that?

00:13:16.280 --> 00:13:18.510
Well, you should simply
interpret it as this.

00:13:18.510 --> 00:13:21.830
Imagine that you
can agree now to buy

00:13:21.830 --> 00:13:27.190
a security that pays $1
just if S&amp;P 500 is up

00:13:27.190 --> 00:13:29.130
at the end of the year.

00:13:29.130 --> 00:13:33.150
And usually when you
and I buy things,

00:13:33.150 --> 00:13:34.650
we buy them in a spot market.

00:13:34.650 --> 00:13:38.600
So we pay now for things.

00:13:38.600 --> 00:13:40.410
But sometimes your
credit is good,

00:13:40.410 --> 00:13:45.000
and you can actually
agree now to pay later.

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:48.270
So, we're going to be thinking
that you're agreeing now

00:13:48.270 --> 00:13:51.440
to pay later some
fixed amount in return

00:13:51.440 --> 00:13:56.550
for the security that's going
to pay $1 just if S&amp;P 500 is up

00:13:56.550 --> 00:13:59.030
at the end of the year.

00:13:59.030 --> 00:14:02.940
And if I tell you that the
risk-neutral probability of S&amp;P

00:14:02.940 --> 00:14:08.190
500 being up by the end
of the year is $0.40,

00:14:08.190 --> 00:14:12.980
what that means financially is
that you agree now to pay $0.40

00:14:12.980 --> 00:14:15.180
at the end of the
year for the security.

00:14:23.640 --> 00:14:26.660
So, you can imagine there'd
be another security that

00:14:26.660 --> 00:14:33.140
pays $1 just if S&amp;P 500 is
down by the end of the year.

00:14:33.140 --> 00:14:41.455
And the only possible price
that that security could have

00:14:41.455 --> 00:14:45.740
in an arbitrage-free
world would be $0.60.

00:14:45.740 --> 00:14:49.520
Because if you were to
buy both securities,

00:14:49.520 --> 00:14:52.330
then you get paid a
total of $0.40 and $0.60.

00:14:52.330 --> 00:14:56.270
So you're agreeing now to pay
$1 at the end of the year.

00:14:56.270 --> 00:14:59.460
And then having both
securities, either S&amp;P is up,

00:14:59.460 --> 00:15:00.930
or S&amp;P is down.

00:15:00.930 --> 00:15:05.820
And so, you collect $1 from
one of them and not the other.

00:15:05.820 --> 00:15:13.840
So if, for example, the one
paying if S&amp;P is up cost $0.40,

00:15:13.840 --> 00:15:17.585
while the one paying if S&amp;P
is down only cost $0.50,

00:15:17.585 --> 00:15:18.960
then there would
be an arbitrage,

00:15:18.960 --> 00:15:21.350
which we would buy
both securities,

00:15:21.350 --> 00:15:22.650
agree now to pay $0.90.

00:15:22.650 --> 00:15:25.140
And then get $1 for sure
at the end of the period.

00:15:25.140 --> 00:15:27.230
So we'd be up $0.10 by
the end of the year.

00:15:27.230 --> 00:15:27.730
Question--

00:15:27.730 --> 00:15:29.688
AUDIENCE: These are
similar to digital options?

00:15:29.688 --> 00:15:31.080
PETER CARR: Yes.

00:15:31.080 --> 00:15:32.439
It's more than similar.

00:15:32.439 --> 00:15:33.480
They are digital options.

00:15:33.480 --> 00:15:33.980
Yeah.

00:15:37.330 --> 00:15:38.477
So, that's right.

00:15:38.477 --> 00:15:40.310
So, that's another term,
which I'll actually

00:15:40.310 --> 00:15:41.880
use on the next slide.

00:15:41.880 --> 00:15:43.550
So, that's exactly right.

00:15:43.550 --> 00:15:46.860
So, digital options is
just too good a term.

00:15:46.860 --> 00:15:49.124
So economists, in order to
obfuscate and look smart,

00:15:49.124 --> 00:15:50.540
call them Arrow-Debreu
securities.

00:15:59.350 --> 00:16:02.170
So, continuing with
the obfuscation,

00:16:02.170 --> 00:16:05.310
I want to tell you about a world
with a representative agent.

00:16:09.480 --> 00:16:12.850
So, economists
are fond of trying

00:16:12.850 --> 00:16:16.450
to formally model the market.

00:16:19.722 --> 00:16:21.450
You read the newspaper.

00:16:21.450 --> 00:16:23.360
Every day, you'll read
something like market

00:16:23.360 --> 00:16:27.840
thought that stocks were no
longer a good investment.

00:16:27.840 --> 00:16:28.840
So there was a sell-off.

00:16:32.720 --> 00:16:34.350
Market is a nice,
short word to capture

00:16:34.350 --> 00:16:35.810
what people are thinking.

00:16:35.810 --> 00:16:37.760
And so economists, rather
than say the market,

00:16:37.760 --> 00:16:40.400
will say there's a world where
the representative agent--

00:16:40.400 --> 00:16:44.930
So this representative agent
is a fictitious investor

00:16:44.930 --> 00:16:51.570
who has all the mathematical
properties that we

00:16:51.570 --> 00:16:54.055
give an investor, such
as utility, function,

00:16:54.055 --> 00:16:57.190
and an endowment, and so on.

00:16:57.190 --> 00:17:00.930
And what makes this
particular investor

00:17:00.930 --> 00:17:04.550
a representative agent is
that this agent sort of

00:17:04.550 --> 00:17:08.680
finds that current
prices are such that it's

00:17:08.680 --> 00:17:16.010
optimal to hold exactly what's
available in the amount that

00:17:16.010 --> 00:17:18.569
is available.

00:17:18.569 --> 00:17:28.650
So if what's on offer is,
let's say, some Google shares,

00:17:28.650 --> 00:17:31.410
and some Apple shares,
and some IBM shares.

00:17:31.410 --> 00:17:36.070
And if we take the total
market cap of Google,

00:17:36.070 --> 00:17:39.370
total market cap of Apple,
total market cap of IBM,

00:17:39.370 --> 00:17:43.420
and, let's say, Apple's biggest.

00:17:43.420 --> 00:17:45.720
I don't actually know whether
Google's bigger or IBM,

00:17:45.720 --> 00:17:47.650
but let's say it's
Google, and then IBM.

00:17:50.920 --> 00:17:53.674
So let's just say Apple's
biggest, then Google, then IBM.

00:17:53.674 --> 00:17:55.090
Well, this investor
would actually

00:17:55.090 --> 00:17:57.100
find that it's optimal
for him to have

00:17:57.100 --> 00:17:59.292
most of his money in
Apple, second most

00:17:59.292 --> 00:18:01.000
of his money in Google,
third most amount

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:04.280
of his money in IBM, that's
the representative agent.

00:18:04.280 --> 00:18:10.250
So, he's acting in the way
the whole economy is acting.

00:18:13.610 --> 00:18:19.540
Well, I've been working in
Wall Street now since 1996.

00:18:19.540 --> 00:18:21.022
I have yet to hear
a trader tell me

00:18:21.022 --> 00:18:22.230
about a representative agent.

00:18:24.950 --> 00:18:28.780
Anyway, so although I
understand what the words mean,

00:18:28.780 --> 00:18:32.840
and even the math, I wanted to
present this material in a way

00:18:32.840 --> 00:18:35.770
that, let's say, at least
quantitative traders

00:18:35.770 --> 00:18:38.450
could understand it.

00:18:38.450 --> 00:18:41.420
So I tried to get away
from representative agents

00:18:41.420 --> 00:18:45.830
and present these
ideas in the language

00:18:45.830 --> 00:18:50.670
that at least quants on Wall
Street are familiar with.

00:18:56.390 --> 00:18:59.590
So, I won't be talking about
a representative agent,

00:18:59.590 --> 00:19:04.320
and I will be talking instead
about something that's probably

00:19:04.320 --> 00:19:08.010
not too familiar to you, but
at least quants have heard of.

00:19:08.010 --> 00:19:11.770
And that would be something
called numeraire portfolio.

00:19:11.770 --> 00:19:14.670
And it also goes by other names.

00:19:14.670 --> 00:19:17.180
Another name is growth
optimal portfolio.

00:19:17.180 --> 00:19:18.940
And it even has a
third name, which

00:19:18.940 --> 00:19:20.590
is called natural numeraire.

00:19:20.590 --> 00:19:22.530
And these are three
different phrases

00:19:22.530 --> 00:19:25.290
that all describe the
same mathematical object.

00:19:25.290 --> 00:19:32.050
And this mathematical object
is a portfolio-- and more

00:19:32.050 --> 00:19:35.310
precisely, it's the
value of a portfolio

00:19:35.310 --> 00:19:38.430
that has some nice properties.

00:19:38.430 --> 00:19:42.010
So the growth optimal
portfolio indicates

00:19:42.010 --> 00:19:44.810
one of its properties.

00:19:44.810 --> 00:19:48.030
This portfolio has a
very nice property,

00:19:48.030 --> 00:19:51.250
which is that in the
long run-- meaning

00:19:51.250 --> 00:19:57.590
over an infinite horizon-- the
growth rate of this portfolio

00:19:57.590 --> 00:19:59.430
is, first of all, random.

00:19:59.430 --> 00:20:04.020
But second, if you take the
mean of that random growth rate,

00:20:04.020 --> 00:20:06.515
that mean is actually
the largest possible

00:20:06.515 --> 00:20:07.390
among all portfolios.

00:20:11.130 --> 00:20:16.500
So, starting with Kelly in
1956, this particular portfolio

00:20:16.500 --> 00:20:21.830
with the largest mean growth
rate over an infinite horizon

00:20:21.830 --> 00:20:24.760
receives a lot of attention.

00:20:24.760 --> 00:20:27.080
It's actually quite humorous,
some of this attention

00:20:27.080 --> 00:20:28.650
that it's received.

00:20:28.650 --> 00:20:31.730
So, Kelly was a physicist
who worked at Bell Labs.

00:20:31.730 --> 00:20:41.140
And he was actually a colleague
of Shannon's at Bell Labs.

00:20:41.140 --> 00:20:44.110
So Shannon did his
seminal work at Bell Labs,

00:20:44.110 --> 00:20:46.700
but actually came
here after that.

00:20:46.700 --> 00:20:57.390
And his ideas really caught
on-- and especially, I'd say,

00:20:57.390 --> 00:21:00.059
started the field of
information science,

00:21:00.059 --> 00:21:01.100
we'll call it-- whatever.

00:21:03.850 --> 00:21:06.990
But Kelly was applying
these ideas to finance.

00:21:06.990 --> 00:21:10.870
And certain financial economists
were less than enthused

00:21:10.870 --> 00:21:14.350
about the application
information of theory

00:21:14.350 --> 00:21:16.820
to finance.

00:21:16.820 --> 00:21:19.670
So, in particular, there was a
financial economist here named

00:21:19.670 --> 00:21:23.590
Paul Samuelson who
championed, I guess,

00:21:23.590 --> 00:21:30.000
the opposition to this
Kelly criterion it's called.

00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:35.427
And so, I'll just tell
you a short story.

