00:24:31.480 --> 00:24:32.740
So there's six
parts to the talk.

00:24:32.740 --> 00:24:34.698
I'm going to go over what
Arrow-Debreu security

00:24:34.698 --> 00:24:38.100
prices are-- so again, they're
digital options prices--

00:24:38.100 --> 00:24:41.210
and their connection
to market beliefs.

00:24:41.210 --> 00:24:43.360
I'll talk about this
Ross recovery theorem.

00:24:43.360 --> 00:24:48.960
So in Ross's paper, which
you can get on SSRN,

00:24:48.960 --> 00:24:54.510
he does everything in a setting
that's called finite state

00:24:54.510 --> 00:24:55.540
Markov chains.

00:24:55.540 --> 00:24:58.640
And so that's
mathematically simpler

00:24:58.640 --> 00:25:01.750
than what we use in practice.

00:25:01.750 --> 00:25:04.760
And I totally agree that
when you try and introduce

00:25:04.760 --> 00:25:08.360
something, you do it in the
simplest mathematical setting.

00:25:08.360 --> 00:25:10.070
So now that he's
done that, I wanted

00:25:10.070 --> 00:25:14.040
to do it in a more
familiar setting, which

00:25:14.040 --> 00:25:17.040
is a diffusion setting.

00:25:17.040 --> 00:25:20.104
A diffusion has an uncountably
infinite number of states.

00:25:20.104 --> 00:25:21.520
And I still want
to keep things as

00:25:21.520 --> 00:25:24.090
simple as possible while
going beyond finite state

00:25:24.090 --> 00:25:24.760
Markov chains.

00:25:24.760 --> 00:25:27.020
So I work in a univariate
diffusion setting.

00:25:27.020 --> 00:25:28.770
So there's only one
source of uncertainty,

00:25:28.770 --> 00:25:30.240
which is the same as in Ross.

00:25:30.240 --> 00:25:37.250
And our technique is
to get these results.

00:25:37.250 --> 00:25:39.440
It's based on something
called change of numeraire.

00:25:39.440 --> 00:25:42.590
So numeraire is a
technical term, actually,

00:25:42.590 --> 00:25:47.160
that describes an asset whose
value is always positive.

00:25:47.160 --> 00:25:55.540
So there are securities whose
values can have either sign.

00:25:55.540 --> 00:25:58.460
So, swaps are a
classical example.

00:25:58.460 --> 00:26:03.070
So a swap is a security which
at inception has zero value,

00:26:03.070 --> 00:26:03.990
actually.

00:26:03.990 --> 00:26:07.140
And then the moment after
inception, the world changes,

00:26:07.140 --> 00:26:09.570
and the swap value
either becomes positive

00:26:09.570 --> 00:26:10.550
or becomes negative.

00:26:13.520 --> 00:26:16.200
So a swap would not
be eligible to be

00:26:16.200 --> 00:26:18.500
a numeraire because
of that property

00:26:18.500 --> 00:26:21.020
that its value is real.

00:26:21.020 --> 00:26:24.030
On the other hand,
if you take a stock,

00:26:24.030 --> 00:26:28.700
its price is always
positive-- well,

00:26:28.700 --> 00:26:37.560
that's debatable actually-- so
let's say let's not do stock.

00:26:37.560 --> 00:26:39.400
Let's do a treasury bond.

00:26:39.400 --> 00:26:43.230
A treasury bond-- US
Treasury bond-- its price

00:26:43.230 --> 00:26:45.910
is always positive.

00:26:45.910 --> 00:26:48.100
The reason I want to
shy away from stocks

00:26:48.100 --> 00:26:51.430
is because we take Lehman
Brothers stock, for example.

00:26:51.430 --> 00:26:53.770
It's price was positive,
then became zero.

00:26:53.770 --> 00:26:56.520
And actually, because
Lehman's price

00:26:56.520 --> 00:27:01.654
became zero, Lehman's share
you could not be a numeraire.

00:27:01.654 --> 00:27:04.070
So when I say that the numeraire
value has to be positive,

00:27:04.070 --> 00:27:05.111
I mean strictly positive.

00:27:09.170 --> 00:27:11.164
And so anyway, there's
this literature

00:27:11.164 --> 00:27:12.580
about how to change
numeraire, how

00:27:12.580 --> 00:27:15.020
to go from one asset
with positive value

00:27:15.020 --> 00:27:17.520
to another asset
with positive value.

00:27:17.520 --> 00:27:20.780
And it's useful
for understanding

00:27:20.780 --> 00:27:22.960
how this Ross recovery works.

00:27:22.960 --> 00:27:29.910
So, we apply it when we have
a so-called time-homogeneous

00:27:29.910 --> 00:27:32.500
diffusion-- and I'll tell
you what that means--

00:27:32.500 --> 00:27:34.000
over a bounded state space.

00:27:34.000 --> 00:27:37.530
So bounded state space
means that the set

00:27:37.530 --> 00:27:40.400
of values that the
diffusion can take

00:27:40.400 --> 00:27:44.090
is in some finite interval.

00:27:44.090 --> 00:27:48.730
So if you're thinking about the
uncertainty being, for example,

00:27:48.730 --> 00:27:53.170
S&amp;P 500, then the natural
lower bound for S&amp;P 500

00:27:53.170 --> 00:27:54.950
would be zero.

00:27:54.950 --> 00:27:58.090
And you have to accept that
there's a finite upper bound

00:27:58.090 --> 00:28:01.050
in order to apply our results.

00:28:01.050 --> 00:28:04.310
Now you know, personally,
I have no problem

00:28:04.310 --> 00:28:08.120
saying the S&amp;P 500 is
bounded above by 20 trillion.

00:28:08.120 --> 00:28:12.190
OK, but some economists
have actually said

00:28:12.190 --> 00:28:14.280
this is ridiculous.

00:28:14.280 --> 00:28:16.540
and challenged my
work, and stuff

00:28:16.540 --> 00:28:20.540
like that for that assumption.

00:28:20.540 --> 00:28:22.300
So, because of those challenges.

00:28:22.300 --> 00:28:24.890
I have actually been
trying to extend

00:28:24.890 --> 00:28:28.470
our work to an unbounded
state space, where, let's say,

00:28:28.470 --> 00:28:32.210
the largest possible value
for S&amp;P 500 would be infinity.

00:28:32.210 --> 00:28:37.280
And I've found, actually,
that it's not that easy.

00:28:37.280 --> 00:28:42.600
And so sometimes, I can make it
work, and sometimes I cannot.

00:28:42.600 --> 00:28:45.740
So, when we get there, I'll
explain some examples that work

00:28:45.740 --> 00:28:47.310
and some examples that don't.

00:28:47.310 --> 00:28:50.950
So this last section is kind of
incomplete, this sixth section.

00:28:50.950 --> 00:28:53.080
And so, basically, I've
got examples that fail,

00:28:53.080 --> 00:28:54.770
examples that succeed.

00:28:54.770 --> 00:28:57.640
But I don't have
a general theory.

00:28:57.640 --> 00:29:00.100
So there'll be
different assumptions

00:29:00.100 --> 00:29:01.410
in different parts of the talk.

00:29:01.410 --> 00:29:03.529
But within a section,
there's only one set

00:29:03.529 --> 00:29:04.570
of assumptions operating,

