00:29:33.650 --> 00:29:34.770
But, anyway--

00:29:34.770 --> 00:29:36.602
AUDIENCE: Actually,
I have some comments

00:29:36.602 --> 00:29:38.900
on the issue of the numeraire.

00:29:38.900 --> 00:29:40.620
You'll tell me
how connected this

00:29:40.620 --> 00:29:44.930
is-- but with the
Kelly criterion, one

00:29:44.930 --> 00:29:48.880
of the origins of that
is if you have a gambling

00:29:48.880 --> 00:29:51.720
opportunity where
it's favorable,

00:29:51.720 --> 00:29:55.650
how much of your bankroll
should you bet on that gamble?

00:29:55.650 --> 00:29:59.860
And basically, the
Kelly criterion

00:29:59.860 --> 00:30:01.610
tells you what proportion
of your bankroll

00:30:01.610 --> 00:30:02.990
you should invest at all times.

00:30:02.990 --> 00:30:04.570
You should never bet everything.

00:30:04.570 --> 00:30:08.080
And if you do bet everything,
you lose everything,

00:30:08.080 --> 00:30:09.670
and you're done.

00:30:09.670 --> 00:30:14.630
So, the issue with the
numeraire portfolio and never

00:30:14.630 --> 00:30:16.690
being able to go down
to zero, in the sense

00:30:16.690 --> 00:30:19.680
that you can never go bankrupt.

00:30:19.680 --> 00:30:24.530
And so, assumptions of
being able to always

00:30:24.530 --> 00:30:27.850
rebalance your portfolio--

00:30:27.850 --> 00:30:29.820
PETER CARR: So, just
give you a flavor

00:30:29.820 --> 00:30:34.600
of what this numeraire
portfolio is--

00:30:34.600 --> 00:30:37.160
you're betting a constant
fraction of your wealth

00:30:37.160 --> 00:30:37.995
in every security.

00:30:40.970 --> 00:30:42.220
So let's just keep it simple.

00:30:42.220 --> 00:30:44.170
There's only two securities.

00:30:44.170 --> 00:30:46.480
One is risky, and
the other's riskless.

00:30:46.480 --> 00:30:50.700
And so you might be betting
putting 40% of your wealth

00:30:50.700 --> 00:30:55.410
in the risky one, and 60%
then in the riskless one.

00:30:55.410 --> 00:30:57.100
And that's when you start.

00:30:57.100 --> 00:31:00.180
So you have $100, and you
put $40 in the risky one,

00:31:00.180 --> 00:31:03.040
and $60 in the riskless one.

00:31:03.040 --> 00:31:07.440
And then, time moves forward.

00:31:07.440 --> 00:31:12.500
And let's say the price
of the risky one changes.

00:31:12.500 --> 00:31:16.780
Then when you revalue
using the new price,

00:31:16.780 --> 00:31:23.930
it's unlikely that 40% of your
wealth is in the risky one.

00:31:23.930 --> 00:31:27.000
So in fact, if the price
went up of the risky one,

00:31:27.000 --> 00:31:30.520
you'll have more than 40% of
your wealth in that risky one.

00:31:30.520 --> 00:31:33.660
So you need to sell
some of that risky one.

00:31:33.660 --> 00:31:36.180
And then the money you get,
you put into the riskless one.

00:31:39.720 --> 00:31:41.650
And so, every time
the price changes,

00:31:41.650 --> 00:31:43.940
you need to trade,
theoretically, in order

00:31:43.940 --> 00:31:49.940
to maintain a constant fraction
of 40% of your wealth invested

00:31:49.940 --> 00:31:51.010
in this risky asset.

00:31:55.410 --> 00:32:00.430
So we assume zero transactions
cost when we do this analysis.

00:32:00.430 --> 00:32:02.360
Because there are positive
transactions cost.

00:32:05.030 --> 00:32:06.710
One should take
that into account.

00:32:06.710 --> 00:32:08.460
And there is literature
on how to do that.

00:32:12.749 --> 00:32:14.790
So, I won't be formally
entertaining transactions

00:32:14.790 --> 00:32:17.610
cost in this talk.

00:32:17.610 --> 00:32:21.620
There's work here at MIT,
actually, on doing that.

00:32:27.880 --> 00:32:30.810
For the question of
how should you invest,

00:32:30.810 --> 00:32:34.330
it feels like it's a
complication that won't change

00:32:34.330 --> 00:32:38.350
anything qualitative about--
it'd definitely change

00:32:38.350 --> 00:32:43.060
how frequently you trade,
but it wouldn't, let's say,

00:32:43.060 --> 00:32:45.900
it's unclear how it would
change your initial investment

00:32:45.900 --> 00:32:47.930
across bets.

00:32:52.440 --> 00:32:54.860
So, let's begin with part one.

00:32:54.860 --> 00:32:58.350
So we have the digital options,
or also called binary options.

00:32:58.350 --> 00:32:59.610
That's another term.

00:32:59.610 --> 00:33:06.610
And they trade, actually, in FX
markets-- so foreign exchange.

00:33:06.610 --> 00:33:10.540
And they pay one unit
of some currencies,

00:33:10.540 --> 00:33:15.587
so say dollar-- If
an event comes true.

00:33:15.587 --> 00:33:17.670
So it might be that you're
looking at dollar/euro.

00:33:17.670 --> 00:33:22.260
And if by the end of the
year, dollar/euro exceeds 2,

00:33:22.260 --> 00:33:23.394
then you get $1.

00:33:23.394 --> 00:33:24.310
Otherwise, you get $0.

00:33:28.740 --> 00:33:31.780
So there would be a
price in the FX markets.

00:33:31.780 --> 00:33:34.740
And it would be a spot
price typically-- so meaning

00:33:34.740 --> 00:33:36.012
you have to pay now for it.

00:33:38.990 --> 00:33:46.620
Let's let A, for arrow, be the
price today of such a security.

00:33:46.620 --> 00:33:50.970
And the subscripts
on A are j given i.

00:33:50.970 --> 00:33:54.450
So, the idea is that you
can think of yourself

00:33:54.450 --> 00:33:57.180
as in a finite-state setting.

00:33:57.180 --> 00:33:59.150
There's various
discrete levels of say,

00:33:59.150 --> 00:34:03.310
dollar/euro that we have
that can be possible today.

00:34:03.310 --> 00:34:05.760
And there's also various
discrete levels for dollar/euro

00:34:05.760 --> 00:34:07.200
by the end of the year.

00:34:07.200 --> 00:34:10.989
And i indicates
the state we're in.

00:34:10.989 --> 00:34:14.100
So maybe dollar euro is
$2 per euro right now.

00:34:16.719 --> 00:34:21.030
And j indicates the
state we can go to.

00:34:21.030 --> 00:34:22.989
Maybe we can go to $3 per euro.

00:34:29.315 --> 00:34:34.250
So in my example, A_(3|2) would
be the price of an Arrow-Debreu

00:34:34.250 --> 00:34:39.323
security, given that the current
dollar euro exchange rate is $2

00:34:39.323 --> 00:34:45.300
per euro, and it pays $1 just if
dollar/euro transitions from $2

00:34:45.300 --> 00:34:47.130
per euro to $3 per euro.

00:34:58.920 --> 00:35:04.420
So the idea is we
have discrete states.

00:35:04.420 --> 00:35:07.300
And let's say these
are values that

00:35:07.300 --> 00:35:11.390
are possible at the
end of the year.

00:35:11.390 --> 00:35:13.710
And the example I just
went through-- you're

00:35:13.710 --> 00:35:20.290
getting $1 just if it's $3 per
euro at the end of the year.

00:35:20.290 --> 00:35:22.440
So the height of that
vertical line is one.

00:35:29.420 --> 00:35:34.360
Now, I'll just
comment that this is

00:35:34.360 --> 00:35:39.510
a slightly exotic option,
in the sense that--

00:35:39.510 --> 00:35:40.670
let's call it exotic.

00:35:40.670 --> 00:35:42.960
It's slightly exotic.

00:35:42.960 --> 00:35:46.570
So in contrast with exotics,
there's this term "vanilla."

00:35:46.570 --> 00:35:49.480
OK, and it actually indicates
a flavor of ice cream.

00:35:52.010 --> 00:35:53.610
So, we have this
terminology which

00:35:53.610 --> 00:35:54.500
you get used to after awhile.

00:35:54.500 --> 00:35:57.041
And you can't understand when
you talk to a man on the street

00:35:57.041 --> 00:36:00.100
why they don't understand
what a vanilla option is.

00:36:00.100 --> 00:36:09.960
So a vanilla option is a
payoff that looks like this--

00:36:09.960 --> 00:36:12.250
so it's a hockey stick payoff.

00:36:12.250 --> 00:36:15.580
And that's the payoff
from a call option.

00:36:15.580 --> 00:36:21.930
And it turns that there is a
portfolio involving options

00:36:21.930 --> 00:36:24.830
at three different
strikes that can perfectly

00:36:24.830 --> 00:36:28.830
replicate the payoff to
this Arrow-Debreu security.

00:36:28.830 --> 00:36:33.900
And so, here is a payoff from
a single option struck at two.

00:36:33.900 --> 00:36:40.480
And I'll just say that if
I had changed the strike

00:36:40.480 --> 00:36:42.533
to, say, be three, then
it would look like that.

00:36:48.690 --> 00:36:51.460
Now, you can combine
options in your portfolio.

00:36:51.460 --> 00:36:55.410
So you could, for example,
buy a call struck at two.

00:36:55.410 --> 00:37:00.570
And then you can furthermore
sell two calls struck at three.

00:37:00.570 --> 00:37:03.350
So if you sell, on top of that,
two calls struck at three,

00:37:03.350 --> 00:37:05.710
you end up creating a
portfolio that goes like this.

00:37:10.380 --> 00:37:13.960
And so, they can go
negative in value.

00:37:13.960 --> 00:37:19.240
So if you not only buy
one call struck at two,

00:37:19.240 --> 00:37:22.340
sell two calls struck at
three, but furthermore,

00:37:22.340 --> 00:37:26.040
buy one call struck
at four, then you

00:37:26.040 --> 00:37:29.390
end up with this payoff,
which the payoff is called

00:37:29.390 --> 00:37:30.640
a butterfly spread payoff.

00:37:30.640 --> 00:37:33.405
Because the picture is meant
to remind you of a butterfly.

00:37:36.430 --> 00:37:42.970
And notice that if the only
possible values for the FX rate

00:37:42.970 --> 00:37:46.600
were $1 per euro or $2 per
euro, or $3 or $4, or $5,

00:37:46.600 --> 00:37:48.110
if that were the world.

00:37:48.110 --> 00:37:53.650
Then notice that when you
formed that portfolio,

00:37:53.650 --> 00:37:56.150
the only positive payoff
you can get from it

00:37:56.150 --> 00:37:58.970
is $1 just if dollar euros at 3.

00:38:03.800 --> 00:38:05.840
You can synthesize a
Arrow-Debreu security

00:38:05.840 --> 00:38:08.880
using a butterfly spread.

00:38:08.880 --> 00:38:11.260
So, this was pointed
out many years ago.

00:38:15.200 --> 00:38:17.040
So even if the FX
market were, let's say,

00:38:17.040 --> 00:38:19.920
not directly giving us the
prices of digital options,

00:38:19.920 --> 00:38:24.630
we could from vanilla options
extract the implicit price

00:38:24.630 --> 00:38:25.370
of a digital.

00:38:32.560 --> 00:38:36.380
And what you would learn
from vanilla options

00:38:36.380 --> 00:38:42.040
is what the market is charging
for the digital, given

00:38:42.040 --> 00:38:46.920
that, let's say, we're
presently at $2 per euro.

00:38:46.920 --> 00:38:51.360
And what you would not
learn from these options

00:38:51.360 --> 00:38:55.660
prices is what the
price of the security

00:38:55.660 --> 00:39:00.430
will be should we today
have the exchange rate

00:39:00.430 --> 00:39:01.625
change to some other value.

00:39:05.550 --> 00:39:07.890
However, you can
make assumptions

00:39:07.890 --> 00:39:10.970
as have what the
options prices will be

00:39:10.970 --> 00:39:13.145
were today's exchange
rate different.

00:39:16.840 --> 00:39:18.745
So, that's commonly
done in practice.

00:39:21.520 --> 00:39:23.860
So a common assumption,
for example,

00:39:23.860 --> 00:39:27.980
is that the probability
of transitioning

00:39:27.980 --> 00:39:35.090
from two to three-- so moving
up by half-- so you're moving up

00:39:35.090 --> 00:39:39.010
by half of two to
three-- is the same

00:39:39.010 --> 00:39:41.160
if you were at any other level.

00:39:41.160 --> 00:39:44.000
So for example, if
you were at four,

00:39:44.000 --> 00:39:46.636
then the probability
of going to six

00:39:46.636 --> 00:39:48.010
would be whatever
the probability

00:39:48.010 --> 00:39:50.080
is of going from two to three.

00:39:50.080 --> 00:39:52.510
Because if you're at four,
the probability of going up

00:39:52.510 --> 00:39:56.990
by half of four to six--
that's the assumption.

00:39:56.990 --> 00:39:59.400
OK, so that's
called sticky delta,

00:39:59.400 --> 00:40:01.720
and it's a common assumption.

00:40:01.720 --> 00:40:03.450
So if you make that
assumption, then you

00:40:03.450 --> 00:40:08.400
can take the information
at just today's level.

00:40:08.400 --> 00:40:13.950
And like, let's say, you know
all the digitals from two,

00:40:13.950 --> 00:40:16.480
and you can make
that assumption.

00:40:16.480 --> 00:40:22.090
Let's say the probability
of a given percentage change

00:40:22.090 --> 00:40:24.430
is invariant to
the starting level.

00:40:24.430 --> 00:40:28.452
And then you can,
from that, figure out

00:40:28.452 --> 00:40:30.910
what the probability of going
from four-- a different level

00:40:30.910 --> 00:40:33.980
than we're at today-- is to
all these different levels.

00:40:33.980 --> 00:40:37.640
So you can go from a
vector bit of information

00:40:37.640 --> 00:40:40.310
that the market is
giving you to a matrix.

00:40:40.310 --> 00:40:43.420
And that matrix is
called transition matrix.

00:40:43.420 --> 00:40:49.020
And so, we're going
to, in this talk,

00:40:49.020 --> 00:40:52.500
assume that somebody's
made such an assumption.

00:40:52.500 --> 00:40:55.120
And so, you actually
know this matrix.

00:40:55.120 --> 00:40:58.510
So you actually know,
as a starting point,

00:40:58.510 --> 00:41:02.440
what the prices are of these
Arrow-Debreu securities

00:41:02.440 --> 00:41:05.900
or binary options
starting from any level

00:41:05.900 --> 00:41:06.960
and going to any level.

00:41:18.650 --> 00:41:24.800
I think in order to get
through my whole talk,

00:41:24.800 --> 00:41:26.915
I'm going to skip these slides.

00:41:26.915 --> 00:41:28.290
Because they're
kind of like just

00:41:28.290 --> 00:41:32.270
being very precise about
what some terms mean

00:41:32.270 --> 00:41:34.540
that aren't going
to be that important

00:41:34.540 --> 00:41:36.520
for the overall story.

00:41:36.520 --> 00:41:41.065
So OK, let's go to this slide.

00:41:44.390 --> 00:41:47.570
So we think of there being just
a single source of uncertainty

00:41:47.570 --> 00:41:49.680
X, which could be dollar/euro.

00:41:49.680 --> 00:41:54.550
And we imagine that we have this
matrix of Arrow-Debreu security

00:41:54.550 --> 00:41:56.060
prices.

00:41:56.060 --> 00:41:58.580
We know every number
in this matrix.

00:41:58.580 --> 00:42:04.750
And we ask what does the market
believe about transitions

00:42:04.750 --> 00:42:08.010
from any place to any place?

00:42:08.010 --> 00:42:10.020
What does the market
believe is the frequency

00:42:10.020 --> 00:42:11.110
of these transitions?

00:42:11.110 --> 00:42:14.860
Now, suppose that
the number that's

00:42:14.860 --> 00:42:18.260
indicating the price of the
Arrow-Debreu security going

00:42:18.260 --> 00:42:24.130
from two to three-- suppose
that number is, say, 0.1.

00:42:24.130 --> 00:42:25.830
Now what does it mean?

00:42:25.830 --> 00:42:30.920
It just means that you pay $0.10
today for security paying $1

00:42:30.920 --> 00:42:33.480
just if you go
from two to three.

00:42:33.480 --> 00:42:35.280
That's all it means.

00:42:35.280 --> 00:42:38.890
Now you can ask what is the
frequency with which you

00:42:38.890 --> 00:42:41.190
go from two to three?

00:42:41.190 --> 00:42:44.700
It need not be 10%.

00:42:44.700 --> 00:42:50.450
There's at least two reasons
why the $0.10 price could differ

00:42:50.450 --> 00:42:54.400
from the probability of going
from where you are to where you

00:42:54.400 --> 00:42:56.680
get paid.

00:42:56.680 --> 00:43:00.030
One such reason is simply
time value of money.

00:43:00.030 --> 00:43:04.650
So if you were to buy all
these Arrow-Debreu securities,

00:43:04.650 --> 00:43:08.420
the one paying off--
one for every state,

00:43:08.420 --> 00:43:13.500
you'll find that the
total cost is less than 1,

00:43:13.500 --> 00:43:16.000
even though the
payoff, for sure,

00:43:16.000 --> 00:43:18.652
is one from the portfolio.

00:43:18.652 --> 00:43:20.860
And that's simply because
of the time value of money.

00:43:20.860 --> 00:43:24.640
So when you put $1
in the bank today,

00:43:24.640 --> 00:43:28.130
you actually get
more than $1 back

00:43:28.130 --> 00:43:29.960
when you pull out at
the end of the year.

00:43:33.140 --> 00:43:34.680
And if you do the
inverse problem--

00:43:34.680 --> 00:43:36.305
how much do you have
to put in the bank

00:43:36.305 --> 00:43:38.880
today in order to have $1
at the end of the year?

00:43:38.880 --> 00:43:44.030
It might be $0.95.

00:43:44.030 --> 00:43:45.780
So that's called
time value of money.

00:43:45.780 --> 00:43:48.740
And so, just the fact
that you have to pay now

00:43:48.740 --> 00:43:49.990
for the Arrow-Debreu security.

00:43:49.990 --> 00:43:54.160
And you only get paid off
at the end of the year.

00:43:54.160 --> 00:44:03.090
That causes this price
of $0.10 to be lower.

00:44:03.090 --> 00:44:06.200
So that's just
discounting for time.

00:44:06.200 --> 00:44:07.660
The interest rates are positive.

00:44:07.660 --> 00:44:09.070
So that's one effect.

00:44:09.070 --> 00:44:15.130
Now there's another effect,
which is called risk aversion.

00:44:15.130 --> 00:44:25.940
So risk aversion is the thought
that even if the interest rate

00:44:25.940 --> 00:44:31.392
was 0, to abstract away from
the effect I just described,

00:44:31.392 --> 00:44:37.780
that it still may be the
case that a $0.10 price paid

00:44:37.780 --> 00:44:41.600
for an Arrow-Debreu security
transitioning from two to three

00:44:41.600 --> 00:44:43.321
is different from the
probability of such

00:44:43.321 --> 00:44:45.320
a transition, the real-world
probability of such

00:44:45.320 --> 00:44:47.260
a transition.

00:44:47.260 --> 00:44:55.350
Because, for example, it may
be quite desirable to get money

00:44:55.350 --> 00:45:01.420
in that state, in which case
$0.10 is over the real-world

00:45:01.420 --> 00:45:03.500
probability.

00:45:03.500 --> 00:45:06.980
Or it could be the opposite that
maybe it's not desirable to get

00:45:06.980 --> 00:45:09.930
money in that state, in
which case $0.10 is under

00:45:09.930 --> 00:45:11.055
the real-world probability.

00:45:14.080 --> 00:45:23.760
So give you a more
concrete example--

00:45:23.760 --> 00:45:26.860
let's say something that is
maybe a little closer to home

00:45:26.860 --> 00:45:31.920
is-- let's say this
is S&amp;P 500, and I

00:45:31.920 --> 00:45:34.540
know the values are very
different than the numbers I've

00:45:34.540 --> 00:45:36.140
indicated here-- but
let's just forget

00:45:36.140 --> 00:45:37.181
about the actual numbers.

00:45:39.860 --> 00:45:43.880
So the point is let's suppose
that it's equally likely,

00:45:43.880 --> 00:45:47.890
in terms of true probabilities,
to go from two to three

00:45:47.890 --> 00:45:49.550
as it is to go from two to one.

00:45:49.550 --> 00:45:52.320
So we have two
Arrow-Debreu securities.

00:45:52.320 --> 00:45:53.240
One struck at one.

00:45:53.240 --> 00:45:55.150
The other struck at three.

00:45:55.150 --> 00:45:57.840
And I'm telling you
that it's equally likely

00:45:57.840 --> 00:46:02.080
that you go up by one as
it is to go down by one.

00:46:02.080 --> 00:46:04.080
Now you can ask the
question does it necessarily

00:46:04.080 --> 00:46:09.140
mean that the prices of
these securities that pay $1

00:46:09.140 --> 00:46:10.260
are the same?

00:46:10.260 --> 00:46:13.020
And the answer is
no, not necessarily.

00:46:13.020 --> 00:46:15.760
And actually, the sort
of standard thinking

00:46:15.760 --> 00:46:20.880
in financial academic
circles is that for S&amp;P 500,

00:46:20.880 --> 00:46:24.680
it would cost more to buy this
Arrow-Debreu security than it

00:46:24.680 --> 00:46:28.360
would cost to buy that
one, even though everyone

00:46:28.360 --> 00:46:32.470
agrees that it's equally likely
to get paid from each of them.

00:46:32.470 --> 00:46:36.850
And the reason that it's
thought to cost more

00:46:36.850 --> 00:46:38.310
to buy this one
than it is to buy

00:46:38.310 --> 00:46:42.110
that one is because this
one has an insurance value.

00:46:42.110 --> 00:46:45.520
So the thinking is that on
average, people are long

00:46:45.520 --> 00:46:49.160
the stocks in the stock
market, and that that

00:46:49.160 --> 00:46:52.340
means that they're really
upset when the stocks fall.

00:46:52.340 --> 00:46:54.660
And so they really
like this one that

00:46:54.660 --> 00:46:59.390
ends up paying should the stock
market fall from two to one,

00:46:59.390 --> 00:47:03.320
whereas this one, while
it's nice to get money,

00:47:03.320 --> 00:47:05.900
let's say you're already
fairly wealthy from the fact

00:47:05.900 --> 00:47:09.590
that you're owning stocks
and the stock market went up.

00:47:09.590 --> 00:47:13.110
So you'll pay a positive
amount for this security,

00:47:13.110 --> 00:47:15.240
but not as much as
you pay for this one.

00:47:19.199 --> 00:47:20.490
So that's called risk aversion.

00:47:24.200 --> 00:47:27.270
So what we want to do is
go from the prices that

00:47:27.270 --> 00:47:31.660
are contaminated, let's say,
by time value of money effects

00:47:31.660 --> 00:47:32.970
and by risk aversion effects.

00:47:32.970 --> 00:47:36.420
And we want to cleanse
them of that contamination

00:47:36.420 --> 00:47:39.130
and try to extract what
the market believes

00:47:39.130 --> 00:47:41.680
are the frequencies
of the future states.

00:47:45.079 --> 00:47:47.370
So I'll tell you that this
was thought to be impossible

00:47:47.370 --> 00:47:50.710
before the Ross
paper, and in fact,

00:47:50.710 --> 00:47:53.440
without making assumptions,
it is impossible.

00:47:53.440 --> 00:47:56.640
So all Ross did is make
some assumptions that

00:47:56.640 --> 00:48:01.880
are thought to be fairly
mild by some, including me.

00:48:01.880 --> 00:48:05.600
And so he essentially,
in essence,

00:48:05.600 --> 00:48:07.330
showed the power of
some assumptions.

00:48:07.330 --> 00:48:08.920
That's one way of
thinking about it.

00:48:15.670 --> 00:48:19.440
So again, let's denote by
R the recovered probability

00:48:19.440 --> 00:48:21.030
measure which will
tell us the market

00:48:21.030 --> 00:48:24.910
beliefs about the
frequencies future state.

00:48:24.910 --> 00:48:28.060
And we don't know
R when we start.

00:48:28.060 --> 00:48:31.050
What we do know is these
Arrow-Debreu security prices,

00:48:31.050 --> 00:48:32.280
I'm assuming.

00:48:32.280 --> 00:48:34.840
And we'll denote
those by A for Arrow.

00:48:38.930 --> 00:48:42.717
So what Ross's paper does
is it says, you know A.

00:48:42.717 --> 00:48:45.050
And if you're willing to make
the following assumptions,

00:48:45.050 --> 00:48:47.280
then you'll know R. So
what are the assumptions?

00:48:47.280 --> 00:48:48.780
Well, before I tell
you assumptions,

00:48:48.780 --> 00:48:51.240
I have to tell you some
terminology so that you

00:48:51.240 --> 00:48:53.670
understand the assumptions.

00:48:53.670 --> 00:48:58.660
So he'll work with a pricing
matrix A, which we've actually

00:48:58.660 --> 00:48:59.800
been going through.

00:48:59.800 --> 00:49:02.530
So that's the Arrow-Debreu
security prices

00:49:02.530 --> 00:49:05.315
index by starting state
and final state, which

00:49:05.315 --> 00:49:08.500
we'll call x is starting
state, y is final state.

00:49:08.500 --> 00:49:10.970
Then there'll be
the desired output

00:49:10.970 --> 00:49:14.100
from this analysis, which
he calls natural probability

00:49:14.100 --> 00:49:15.320
transition matrix.

00:49:15.320 --> 00:49:19.310
So these are the markets
beliefs for every starting value

00:49:19.310 --> 00:49:22.180
x and for every final value y.

00:49:22.180 --> 00:49:25.180
And then there'll be something
called pricing kernel,

00:49:25.180 --> 00:49:28.610
which is literally the ratio
of these Arrow-Debreu security

00:49:28.610 --> 00:49:35.140
prices to these output
natural probabilities.

00:49:35.140 --> 00:49:37.790
So, if you want to get
an understanding of what

00:49:37.790 --> 00:49:40.290
this pricing kernel
is, you can think of it

00:49:40.290 --> 00:49:46.220
as an attempt to
capture the effects

00:49:46.220 --> 00:49:50.100
from time value of money
and from risk aversion.

00:49:50.100 --> 00:49:53.050
So think of it as
a normalization.

00:49:53.050 --> 00:49:55.970
You start with A,
and A is actually

00:49:55.970 --> 00:49:57.170
affected by three things.

00:49:57.170 --> 00:50:00.940
It's affected by the
unknown real world

00:50:00.940 --> 00:50:04.466
probabilities-- or at least
markets beliefs of them.

00:50:04.466 --> 00:50:06.530
A is also affected
by a second thing,

00:50:06.530 --> 00:50:08.200
which is time value of money.

00:50:08.200 --> 00:50:11.300
And A is affected by a third
thing, which is risk aversion.

00:50:11.300 --> 00:50:15.760
So if we take A and
divide by P, then we're

00:50:15.760 --> 00:50:19.320
normalizing for the first
effect, the frequencies.

00:50:19.320 --> 00:50:23.200
And so we're left with
just the combined effect

00:50:23.200 --> 00:50:26.110
from time value of money
and from risk aversion.

00:50:28.890 --> 00:50:34.870
And so, let's say, if interest
rate were zero and people

00:50:34.870 --> 00:50:40.990
were risk neutral, then we would
actually expect A to equal P.

00:50:40.990 --> 00:50:42.775
And so this ratio
would be just constant.

00:50:48.800 --> 00:50:53.630
So Ross talks about a world
with a representative investor.

00:50:53.630 --> 00:51:01.650
And essentially, this is an
assumption-- this equation

00:51:01.650 --> 00:51:02.590
you're seeing here.

00:51:06.950 --> 00:51:10.070
It's an assumption on
the form that a function

00:51:10.070 --> 00:51:11.170
of two variables takes.

00:51:11.170 --> 00:51:14.600
So phi, first of all,
is a positive function.

00:51:14.600 --> 00:51:18.760
So phi is positive, as opposed
to-- so phi cannot take

00:51:18.760 --> 00:51:21.680
negative values because
both A and P are positive.

00:51:21.680 --> 00:51:27.130
And phi is a function of
two variables-- x and y.

00:51:27.130 --> 00:51:29.850
And what this assumption
is doing is it's saying,

00:51:29.850 --> 00:51:33.520
well, let's put structure
on this function phi

00:51:33.520 --> 00:51:36.450
because it'll help us to find
it if we put the structure.

00:51:36.450 --> 00:51:39.380
So this is the first key
assumption actually--

00:51:39.380 --> 00:51:44.210
that the function of two
variables x and y actually

00:51:44.210 --> 00:51:47.680
has the form on the right,
which, for a moment,

00:51:47.680 --> 00:51:49.764
just ignore the
delta for a moment.

00:51:49.764 --> 00:51:51.930
And then you can see that
what you have on the right

00:51:51.930 --> 00:51:54.570
if you ignore delta, if
you think of delta as one,

00:51:54.570 --> 00:51:56.840
is you have a function of y.

00:51:56.840 --> 00:51:59.000
And then you have the
same function of x.

00:51:59.000 --> 00:52:02.489
So it's written in a convoluted
way with this U prime, and c,

00:52:02.489 --> 00:52:03.280
and all that stuff.

00:52:03.280 --> 00:52:07.340
But if delta's one, then you
have a fraction whose numerator

00:52:07.340 --> 00:52:09.190
is a function of y
and whose denominator

00:52:09.190 --> 00:52:10.710
is the same function, but of x.

00:52:17.550 --> 00:52:20.590
In essence, what that
does is it reduces

00:52:20.590 --> 00:52:23.950
the dimensionality of the thing
we're searching for by a lot.

00:52:23.950 --> 00:52:27.170
So we started by searching for
a function phi of two variables.

00:52:27.170 --> 00:52:29.970
And we, by this assumption,
reduced the search

00:52:29.970 --> 00:52:31.840
to a function of
one variable, which

00:52:31.840 --> 00:52:34.030
is, say, the function
in the numerator, which

00:52:34.030 --> 00:52:35.988
is the same as the function
in the denominator.

00:52:38.640 --> 00:52:41.170
So, now let's bring back delta.

00:52:41.170 --> 00:52:45.460
And delta's a scalar here,
and it's a positive scalar.

00:52:45.460 --> 00:52:47.970
And so we need to
search for that as well.

00:52:47.970 --> 00:52:50.080
So in the end, we
reduce the search

00:52:50.080 --> 00:52:54.850
to a function of one
variable and a scalar delta.

00:52:54.850 --> 00:52:59.700
So the economic meaning
of, first of all,

00:52:59.700 --> 00:53:01.550
the function of
one variable is--

00:53:01.550 --> 00:53:03.930
it's called marginal utility.

00:53:03.930 --> 00:53:07.410
And it's meant to indicate
how much happiness you

00:53:07.410 --> 00:53:11.210
get from each additional
unit of consumption.

00:53:11.210 --> 00:53:14.250
So it's the typical--
what we think

00:53:14.250 --> 00:53:22.420
it looks like as a function of
c-- U prime as a function of c

00:53:22.420 --> 00:53:24.180
is thought to typically
look like that.

00:53:24.180 --> 00:53:26.760
So it's positive, meaning
every unit of consumption

00:53:26.760 --> 00:53:27.840
makes you happy.

00:53:27.840 --> 00:53:31.750
And it's actually
declining, meaning

00:53:31.750 --> 00:53:34.366
the first unit of consumption
makes you real happy.

00:53:34.366 --> 00:53:35.740
Then the next unit
of consumption

00:53:35.740 --> 00:53:38.310
still brings some happiness,
but not as much, and so on.

00:53:41.750 --> 00:53:43.870
So that's the kind of
function we're looking for.

00:53:43.870 --> 00:53:46.990
U prime as a function of c.

00:53:46.990 --> 00:53:50.520
He won't actually find U
prime as a function of c.

00:53:50.520 --> 00:53:56.840
He'll find the composition of
U prime with a function c of y.

00:54:01.920 --> 00:54:05.030
Keep that in mind.

00:54:05.030 --> 00:54:06.710
Then, there's that delta.

00:54:06.710 --> 00:54:10.260
And that's, again,
a positive scalar.

00:54:10.260 --> 00:54:14.540
And it's meant to capture
time value of money.

00:54:14.540 --> 00:54:21.497
And so, that's like the y is the
state at the end of the period.

00:54:21.497 --> 00:54:23.580
And x is the state at the
beginning of the period.

00:54:23.580 --> 00:54:26.230
And so, that's why delta's
associated with the numerator,

00:54:26.230 --> 00:54:27.790
not the denominator.

00:54:27.790 --> 00:54:30.020
So delta would be
a number like 0.9.

00:54:30.020 --> 00:54:35.340
And that indicates how
much discount you give to,

00:54:35.340 --> 00:54:38.890
let's say happiness received
in the future, rather than now.

00:54:42.760 --> 00:54:50.380
Now, here's a quote from Ross's
paper that is his Theorem 1.

00:54:50.380 --> 00:54:52.150
That's called the
recovery theorem.

00:54:52.150 --> 00:54:56.480
And the only thing is
I changed the letters

00:54:56.480 --> 00:54:58.840
to conform with the
letters I'm using,

00:54:58.840 --> 00:55:00.224
rather than the ones he used.

00:55:00.224 --> 00:55:01.890
And that's because
his choice of letters

00:55:01.890 --> 00:55:06.520
is completely unnatural
to me and most people.

00:55:06.520 --> 00:55:10.440
So I don't even want to
tell you what he used.

00:55:10.440 --> 00:55:13.980
So anyway, whereas I tried to
choose letters that make sense.

00:55:13.980 --> 00:55:15.160
So I used A for Debreu--

00:55:20.381 --> 00:55:21.880
So anyway, he says,
you have a world

00:55:21.880 --> 00:55:23.046
with a representative agent.

00:55:23.046 --> 00:55:28.630
So that's actually
this restriction

00:55:28.630 --> 00:55:31.130
that we talked about
on the last slide.

00:55:31.130 --> 00:55:34.750
And then he says, if the
pricing matrix-- which

00:55:34.750 --> 00:55:37.980
is the Arrow-Debreu security
prices-- is positive--

00:55:37.980 --> 00:55:39.640
which means that
all entries in it

00:55:39.640 --> 00:55:43.020
are strictly above
zero-- or irreducible--

00:55:43.020 --> 00:55:46.060
which means that some
entries have zeros,

00:55:46.060 --> 00:55:48.700
with the rest being
positive, and there's

00:55:48.700 --> 00:55:50.990
some structure, which we
need not get into where

00:55:50.990 --> 00:55:56.840
the zeros are-- then there
exists a unique solution

00:55:56.840 --> 00:56:01.880
of the problem of finding
P, which P is actually

00:56:01.880 --> 00:56:02.750
market beliefs.

00:56:02.750 --> 00:56:05.630
And I've been
calling that R often.

00:56:05.630 --> 00:56:08.160
So anyway, I slipped a
bit there and called it P.

00:56:08.160 --> 00:56:11.950
So anyway, that's market
beliefs about the frequencies

00:56:11.950 --> 00:56:13.170
of future states.

00:56:13.170 --> 00:56:15.600
He'll also get as
an output the delta,

00:56:15.600 --> 00:56:19.590
which is the positive scalar
telling you the market's time

00:56:19.590 --> 00:56:20.380
value of money.

00:56:20.380 --> 00:56:24.010
And finally, this
pricing kernel phi,

00:56:24.010 --> 00:56:35.397
which is the ratio
of A to P. So,

00:56:35.397 --> 00:56:37.980
what you're supposed to realize,
even though he didn't say it,

00:56:37.980 --> 00:56:42.107
is that as a result-- well, OK.

00:56:42.107 --> 00:56:43.190
So he did say it actually.

00:56:43.190 --> 00:56:45.230
You're finding P. I think
that's the main thing.

00:56:49.630 --> 00:56:54.440
He's actually saying, if
you make these assumptions,

00:56:54.440 --> 00:57:03.370
surprisingly, there's only one
possible real world or market

00:57:03.370 --> 00:57:06.909
beliefs that are
consistent with the data

00:57:06.909 --> 00:57:07.950
and the assumptions made.

00:57:12.240 --> 00:57:15.240
To give you a sense of what
the importance of this result

00:57:15.240 --> 00:57:19.260
is-- so prior to
his paper-- I mean,

00:57:19.260 --> 00:57:21.300
people have been
interested in trying

00:57:21.300 --> 00:57:25.560
to infer from market prices
what the market believes.

00:57:25.560 --> 00:57:27.860
But they always
thought that you had

00:57:27.860 --> 00:57:34.300
to supply some parameters that
capture market risk aversion.

00:57:34.300 --> 00:57:36.100
So for example,
common approach is

00:57:36.100 --> 00:57:40.520
to assume that you have a
representative investor.

00:57:40.520 --> 00:57:42.210
And that they have
a particular type

00:57:42.210 --> 00:57:45.420
of utility function called
constant relative risk

00:57:45.420 --> 00:57:46.280
aversion.

00:57:46.280 --> 00:57:48.375
And there's a parameter
in that utility function.

00:57:48.375 --> 00:57:50.750
And you had to specify the
numerical value that parameter

00:57:50.750 --> 00:57:57.800
takes before you could learn the
market's beliefs from prices.

00:57:57.800 --> 00:58:00.130
And no one ever felt
very comfortable

00:58:00.130 --> 00:58:02.270
specifying that parameter.

00:58:02.270 --> 00:58:10.300
So what Ross essentially did
is he managed to essentially do

00:58:10.300 --> 00:58:15.080
the identification
non-parametrically, where

00:58:15.080 --> 00:58:17.330
you don't have to
supply any parameters.

00:58:17.330 --> 00:58:25.040
And so you essentially just
have to buy his assumptions.

00:58:25.040 --> 00:58:31.480
You don't have to do any work to
actually go from market prices

00:58:31.480 --> 00:58:33.070
to market's beliefs.

00:58:40.490 --> 00:58:42.160
OK, so let's skip these remarks.

00:58:44.790 --> 00:58:45.290
Yeah.

00:58:45.290 --> 00:58:49.170
AUDIENCE: Can you
elaborate on the fact

00:58:49.170 --> 00:58:52.460
that risk aversion
does enter in?

00:58:55.032 --> 00:58:55.740
PETER CARR: Yeah.

00:58:55.740 --> 00:58:57.350
So the exact
statement is you don't

00:58:57.350 --> 00:59:02.440
have to supply a
parameter that describes

00:59:02.440 --> 00:59:05.910
the amount of the
market's risk aversion.

00:59:05.910 --> 00:59:11.060
Rather you have to
accept this assumption--

00:59:11.060 --> 00:59:14.030
and I'll show you--
this assumption

00:59:14.030 --> 00:59:16.230
about the structure of phi.

00:59:16.230 --> 00:59:21.200
OK, so if you just accept that
this function of two variables

00:59:21.200 --> 00:59:26.220
doesn't have the full
amount of degrees of freedom

00:59:26.220 --> 00:59:28.670
that an arbitrary function
two variables has,

00:59:28.670 --> 00:59:30.140
it has a reduced
number of degrees

00:59:30.140 --> 00:59:33.880
of freedom implicit on
the right-hand side.

00:59:33.880 --> 00:59:38.140
So remembering
that x is actually

00:59:38.140 --> 00:59:42.730
just a vector of finite
length and so is y,

00:59:42.730 --> 00:59:45.460
then think of the left-hand side
as having degrees of freedom n

00:59:45.460 --> 00:59:47.400
squared.

00:59:47.400 --> 00:59:49.310
And on the right-hand
side, you're

00:59:49.310 --> 00:59:54.070
looking for the numerator
function is just

00:59:54.070 --> 00:59:56.060
a vector of length n.

00:59:56.060 --> 01:00:00.600
And the denominator function
is the same function, so

01:00:00.600 --> 01:00:01.570
the same vector.

01:00:01.570 --> 01:00:04.140
And then there's
also this delta.

01:00:04.140 --> 01:00:06.330
So let's say on
the left-hand side,

01:00:06.330 --> 01:00:09.450
you're describing something
that without restriction is

01:00:09.450 --> 01:00:10.880
of order n squared.

01:00:10.880 --> 01:00:14.410
So let's say n is 10, so it
has 100 degrees of freedom.

01:00:14.410 --> 01:00:15.890
And on the right-hand
side, you're

01:00:15.890 --> 01:00:20.140
describing a vector of length
10 along with a scalar--

01:00:20.140 --> 01:00:21.800
so 11 degrees of freedom.

01:00:21.800 --> 01:00:23.370
So you have to
accept that you're

01:00:23.370 --> 01:00:26.890
willing to before you
place any restriction,

01:00:26.890 --> 01:00:28.290
it's 100 degrees of freedom.

01:00:28.290 --> 01:00:29.540
Now you make your restriction.

01:00:29.540 --> 01:00:30.040
It's 11.

01:00:30.040 --> 01:00:31.540
You have to accept that.

01:00:31.540 --> 01:00:39.255
And if you do, then he'll
tell you the 11 entries.

01:00:39.255 --> 01:00:39.780
That's it.

01:00:39.780 --> 01:00:41.321
So you don't have
to supply anything.

01:00:43.560 --> 01:00:45.310
So I haven't told you
how we'll find them.

01:00:45.310 --> 01:00:46.672
That's probably what you're
asking-- how the hell

01:00:46.672 --> 01:00:47.590
will you get to 11?

01:00:47.590 --> 01:00:48.960
OK, so I haven't shown you that.

01:00:48.960 --> 01:00:49.460
Yes?

01:00:49.460 --> 01:00:52.750
AUDIENCE: Just really
quickly, the c change

01:00:52.750 --> 01:00:55.200
as a function of
time and spot price?

01:00:55.200 --> 01:00:58.880
PETER CARR: c is not
a function of time,

01:00:58.880 --> 01:01:01.710
to answer your question.

01:01:01.710 --> 01:01:08.910
And then, the argument
of c could be a price.

01:01:08.910 --> 01:01:11.150
It's allowed to be a price.

01:01:11.150 --> 01:01:12.710
OK?

01:01:12.710 --> 01:01:16.620
So, that's how you
should think of it.

01:01:16.620 --> 01:01:19.670
So there's a lot of time
homogeneity in everything

01:01:19.670 --> 01:01:20.540
he does here.

01:01:20.540 --> 01:01:24.000
So he'll never let anything
depend on time, actually,

01:01:24.000 --> 01:01:25.030
to answer your question.

01:01:31.820 --> 01:01:36.930
So, I still haven't
shown you how he did it.

01:01:36.930 --> 01:01:38.320
He uses Perron-Frobenius
theorem.

01:01:41.620 --> 01:01:43.710
I don't actually have
slides on how you actually

01:01:43.710 --> 01:01:46.990
calculate the 11 entries.

01:01:46.990 --> 01:01:49.960
So I think I just have to
refer you to the paper.

01:01:49.960 --> 01:01:52.860
But he relies on
something called

01:01:52.860 --> 01:01:54.250
Perron-Frobenius theorem.

01:01:54.250 --> 01:02:00.010
And I'm going to show
you how we-- my co-author

01:02:00.010 --> 01:02:08.040
and I-- actually
calculate the analog

01:02:08.040 --> 01:02:09.750
of that 11-dimensional unknown.

01:02:12.840 --> 01:02:16.670
So we're going to work in
a continuous setting, where

01:02:16.670 --> 01:02:19.520
instead of looking for
a vector and a scalar,

01:02:19.520 --> 01:02:22.080
we're going to look for
a function, and a scalar,

01:02:22.080 --> 01:02:23.970
and a function of one variable.

01:02:28.530 --> 01:02:31.120
So you'll get a sense of
how to do it from ours.

01:02:31.120 --> 01:02:33.130
And essentially, if you
discretize what we do,

01:02:33.130 --> 01:02:34.088
you'll get what he did.

01:02:37.670 --> 01:02:41.220
Let's forget these remarks,
and let's forget these.

01:02:41.220 --> 01:02:45.410
And so now, we'll
get into some theory

01:02:45.410 --> 01:02:46.910
about changing numeraire.

01:02:46.910 --> 01:02:53.095
So this is a backdrop to how
my co-author and I proceed.

01:02:59.280 --> 01:03:02.720
So again, a numeraire is
a portfolio whose value

01:03:02.720 --> 01:03:04.790
is always strictly positive.

01:03:04.790 --> 01:03:08.986
And there is a
well-developed theory

01:03:08.986 --> 01:03:11.360
in derivatives pricing about
how to change the numeraire.

01:03:16.080 --> 01:03:20.500
We're going to use that theory
to understand what Ross did.

01:03:20.500 --> 01:03:24.590
So we start with an economy
with a so-called money market

01:03:24.590 --> 01:03:25.620
account.

01:03:25.620 --> 01:03:28.650
And so that's a
theoretical construct

01:03:28.650 --> 01:03:34.900
that's pretty familiar to most
of us, and it's a bank account.

01:03:34.900 --> 01:03:38.160
So we're going to be working
now in continuous time.

01:03:38.160 --> 01:03:41.830
So imagine that time, which is
continuous, is on this axis.

01:03:41.830 --> 01:03:43.710
And then we're
sitting here today,

01:03:43.710 --> 01:03:45.580
and we put some
money into the bank.

01:03:45.580 --> 01:03:49.160
And being poor,
we only put $1 in.

01:03:49.160 --> 01:03:55.400
So then we ask, looking forward,
how will this money in our bank

01:03:55.400 --> 01:03:56.660
change?

01:03:56.660 --> 01:04:01.680
Well, they do still pay
a positive interest rate,

01:04:01.680 --> 01:04:04.030
and it's awfully small,
but it's positive.

01:04:04.030 --> 01:04:05.920
And so it'll go up.

01:04:05.920 --> 01:04:08.680
And they change
the rate actually.

01:04:08.680 --> 01:04:12.290
So now, maybe it's 0.5%,
but next week, Chase

01:04:12.290 --> 01:04:15.980
might decide to give you 1%, in
which case it goes up faster.

01:04:15.980 --> 01:04:17.940
And then they might the
week after give you 2%,

01:04:17.940 --> 01:04:18.705
it goes up faster.

01:04:18.705 --> 01:04:20.530
Then they might go back to 0.5%.

01:04:20.530 --> 01:04:24.150
So that's one possible path
for your money market account

01:04:24.150 --> 01:04:25.060
balance.

01:04:25.060 --> 01:04:27.950
And we don't know the future.

01:04:27.950 --> 01:04:30.811
We know how much we're getting
over this first little bit

01:04:30.811 --> 01:04:31.310
of time.

01:04:31.310 --> 01:04:33.510
But they could
actually decide to pay

01:04:33.510 --> 01:04:37.051
less over the second period,
and then the third, or something

01:04:37.051 --> 01:04:37.550
like that.

01:04:37.550 --> 01:04:40.899
OK, so it's increasing
and it's random.

01:04:40.899 --> 01:04:42.690
So that's the money
market account balance.

01:04:42.690 --> 01:04:48.660
It's considered as an
increasing, random process.

01:04:48.660 --> 01:04:50.835
And actually, there's
nothing in the math that

01:04:50.835 --> 01:04:55.260
requires it to be increasing
if some really cheap bank--

01:04:55.260 --> 01:04:57.480
like Bank of America
tried this actually--

01:04:57.480 --> 01:05:00.100
charge a negative rate.

01:05:00.100 --> 01:05:03.164
Then it would actually go
down with a negative rate.

01:05:03.164 --> 01:05:04.330
But it wouldn't go negative.

01:05:04.330 --> 01:05:06.280
So it's still counts
as a numeraire.

01:05:09.240 --> 01:05:11.760
So anyway, that's
allowed, as an aside.

01:05:14.439 --> 01:05:16.230
OK, so we've got this
money market account.

01:05:19.410 --> 01:05:23.610
So the growth rate is called
r, and that's just real-valued.

01:05:23.610 --> 01:05:25.480
And then we also
have risky asset.

01:05:25.480 --> 01:05:29.060
So we'll have a total
of n risky assets.

01:05:29.060 --> 01:05:32.690
And then we're
going to say there's

01:05:32.690 --> 01:05:35.985
no arbitrage between the n risky
assets and the one money market

01:05:35.985 --> 01:05:36.485
account.

01:05:43.290 --> 01:05:46.030
The idea is that we look
at Bloomberg's prices

01:05:46.030 --> 01:05:49.570
for these n plus 1 assets,
we're able to extract

01:05:49.570 --> 01:05:51.670
the Arrow-Debreu
security prices.

01:05:51.670 --> 01:05:52.390
That's the idea.

01:05:55.610 --> 01:05:59.960
What I'm assuming is that
what we're extracting

01:05:59.960 --> 01:06:04.330
is consistent with the idea
that the uncertainty that's

01:06:04.330 --> 01:06:07.070
driving everything here
is a diffusion, meaning

01:06:07.070 --> 01:06:15.620
that the uncertainty has sample
paths that are continuous,

01:06:15.620 --> 01:06:18.300
but they're allowed
to be fairly jagged.

01:06:18.300 --> 01:06:20.520
So diffusions actually
have continuous but

01:06:20.520 --> 01:06:22.820
non-differentiable sample paths.

01:06:22.820 --> 01:06:24.600
And we're going to assume that.

01:06:24.600 --> 01:06:26.930
So this is a common assumption.

01:06:26.930 --> 01:06:32.130
This basically got
its start here at MIT.

01:06:32.130 --> 01:06:37.750
And diffusions were first
used in a finance context

01:06:37.750 --> 01:06:42.090
back in 1965 when both
Samuelson and McKean were here.

01:06:42.090 --> 01:06:43.640
So McKean is a probabilist.

01:06:43.640 --> 01:06:47.940
He's now at NYU where I
teach, and he's still active.

01:06:47.940 --> 01:06:52.680
And diffusions are widely used.

01:06:52.680 --> 01:06:55.380
So they really got
a big boost in 1973

01:06:55.380 --> 01:06:58.897
when Black-Scholes and
Merton, who were all here,

01:06:58.897 --> 01:07:01.480
used the diffusion to describe
the price of a stock underlying

01:07:01.480 --> 01:07:02.570
an option.

01:07:02.570 --> 01:07:06.440
And since then, they've
just been used extensively

01:07:06.440 --> 01:07:07.580
in finance.

01:07:07.580 --> 01:07:12.440
So Merton, who's
here, really, I'd say,

01:07:12.440 --> 01:07:14.730
pioneered the use
of them in finance.

01:07:29.840 --> 01:07:33.210
So there's this
uncertainty X is probably

01:07:33.210 --> 01:07:37.300
mysterious to you,
hence the name X.

01:07:37.300 --> 01:07:39.180
So it's like, you
get to choose what

01:07:39.180 --> 01:07:40.380
it is, is kind of the idea.

01:07:40.380 --> 01:07:42.400
So this is theory.

01:07:42.400 --> 01:07:46.990
And it's not trying to be
overly specific so that you can

01:07:46.990 --> 01:07:50.310
apply it in different contexts.

01:07:50.310 --> 01:07:52.920
But you'd like to know at
least some examples, I'm sure.

01:07:52.920 --> 01:07:56.940
So one example would be X
is the level of S&amp;P 500.

01:07:56.940 --> 01:08:02.470
A different example would be X
is actually an interest rate.

01:08:02.470 --> 01:08:05.650
So let's say the
benchmark 30 year yield.

01:08:08.280 --> 01:08:11.710
X could instead be a
shorter-term interest rate,

01:08:11.710 --> 01:08:18.200
something called OIS--
overnight index swap-- is

01:08:18.200 --> 01:08:20.540
a possible choice for x.

01:08:23.439 --> 01:08:25.120
When I apply Ross's
stuff, that's

01:08:25.120 --> 01:08:28.340
how I choose X, as a
short-term interest rate.

01:08:32.850 --> 01:08:36.350
In general, let's say I
developed a theory that

01:08:36.350 --> 01:08:38.410
says the short-rate
of some function of X.

01:08:38.410 --> 01:08:40.300
And when I actually
apply it, the function

01:08:40.300 --> 01:08:41.200
is the identity map.

01:08:51.160 --> 01:08:56.520
The mathematics says that
if there's no arbitrage,

01:08:56.520 --> 01:09:00.063
then there exists-- as
we're assuming-- then

01:09:00.063 --> 01:09:02.229
there exists this so-called
risk-neutral probability

01:09:02.229 --> 01:09:06.890
measure that I talked about
earlier and denoted by Q.

01:09:06.890 --> 01:09:09.600
It's related but not equal
to the Arrow-Debreu security

01:09:09.600 --> 01:09:10.439
prices.

01:09:10.439 --> 01:09:14.700
So if you were to just
imagine that instead

01:09:14.700 --> 01:09:17.620
of buying these Arrow-Debreu
security prices in a spot

01:09:17.620 --> 01:09:20.350
market, if you instead bought
them in a forward market

01:09:20.350 --> 01:09:23.050
where you actually
pay when they mature,

01:09:23.050 --> 01:09:27.310
then those Arrow-Debreu security
prices in the forward market

01:09:27.310 --> 01:09:31.609
would be Q. So Q and
A are really close.

01:09:31.609 --> 01:09:36.392
So the measure A need
not integrate to one,

01:09:36.392 --> 01:09:38.350
and that's just due to
the time value of money,

01:09:38.350 --> 01:09:39.935
and that's because you're
paying in the spot market.

01:09:39.935 --> 01:09:41.590
If you're actually paying
in the forward market,

01:09:41.590 --> 01:09:43.881
then you don't have to worry
about time value of money.

01:09:43.881 --> 01:09:46.422
And so then, the measure
Q does integrate to one.

01:09:46.422 --> 01:09:48.380
So that's why we call it
a probability measure.

01:09:53.300 --> 01:09:55.570
Under this
probability measure Q,

01:09:55.570 --> 01:09:59.290
the expected return on all
assets is the risk-free rate.

01:09:59.290 --> 01:10:02.910
So that's what that actually
says, although you're probably

01:10:02.910 --> 01:10:05.350
not seeing that this is
literally the expected

01:10:05.350 --> 01:10:08.340
return-- well more precisely,
it's expected price change.

01:10:08.340 --> 01:10:09.810
So the expected
price change is--

01:10:09.810 --> 01:10:12.462
what that means is
expected price change is

01:10:12.462 --> 01:10:13.920
the risk-free rate
times the price.

01:10:13.920 --> 01:10:16.510
That's what that says.

01:10:16.510 --> 01:10:18.550
So if you divide both
sides by the spot price

01:10:18.550 --> 01:10:21.290
when it's positive, then
you'll get the expected return

01:10:21.290 --> 01:10:23.170
is equal to risk-free rate.

01:10:23.170 --> 01:10:25.280
And we're doing things
in continuous time here.

01:10:25.280 --> 01:10:27.960
So we're working
with diffusions.

01:10:27.960 --> 01:10:30.420
And you may or may not
have been introduced

01:10:30.420 --> 01:10:33.260
to diffusions at this stage
in your mathematical career.

01:10:33.260 --> 01:10:36.590
But mathematically, one
way to describe diffusion

01:10:36.590 --> 01:10:39.500
is via the
infinitesimal generator.

01:10:39.500 --> 01:10:42.750
So this is a
differential operator

01:10:42.750 --> 01:10:46.620
that's first order in time,
second order in space.

01:10:46.620 --> 01:10:50.090
And let's just say this is
formally how mathematicians

01:10:50.090 --> 01:10:53.250
think about this type of thing.

01:10:53.250 --> 01:10:56.370
What I've drawn here is a
single sample path of diffusion.

01:10:56.370 --> 01:10:58.830
There's definitely possibility
of other sample paths.

01:10:58.830 --> 01:11:00.788
These actually are an
infinite number of paths.

01:11:00.788 --> 01:11:04.760
But they're all continuous
and nowhere differentiable.

01:11:22.454 --> 01:11:24.120
I want to just kind
of give you a flavor

01:11:24.120 --> 01:11:27.350
of how you change numeraires.

01:11:27.350 --> 01:11:29.850
So we started with the
numeraire being the money

01:11:29.850 --> 01:11:31.530
market account-- this guy.

01:11:31.530 --> 01:11:33.289
And the idea is
we're going to switch

01:11:33.289 --> 01:11:34.330
to a different numeraire.

01:11:39.640 --> 01:11:42.790
What we're mainly
interested in figuring out

01:11:42.790 --> 01:11:58.960
is what are the drifts of assets
when we measure their values

01:11:58.960 --> 01:12:00.530
in a different numeraire.

01:12:00.530 --> 01:12:04.480
So I've kind of given you a
sense of what this is about.

01:12:04.480 --> 01:12:11.250
So you could hold IBM, and
every time you get a gain,

01:12:11.250 --> 01:12:14.790
you could put that gain in
your local bank-- Chase--

01:12:14.790 --> 01:12:18.660
and see how fast your
bank balance grows

01:12:18.660 --> 01:12:23.130
as you're putting all your
gains in IBM in the bank.

01:12:23.130 --> 01:12:28.630
And you'll get a certain
growth rate from that strategy.

01:12:28.630 --> 01:12:30.980
Now, you could try a
different strategy where

01:12:30.980 --> 01:12:32.670
you take your gains from IBM.

01:12:32.670 --> 01:12:36.600
And you actually ship them off
over to a British bank, which

01:12:36.600 --> 01:12:40.000
is denominated in
pounds, and see how fast

01:12:40.000 --> 01:12:41.960
that bank balance grows.

01:12:41.960 --> 01:12:45.160
And there's no reason that
the two bank balances--

01:12:45.160 --> 01:12:46.800
the American one and
the British one--

01:12:46.800 --> 01:12:48.580
need to grow at the same rate.

01:12:48.580 --> 01:12:51.940
Because they're denominated
in different currencies.

01:12:51.940 --> 01:12:55.410
So we're basically
interested to know,

01:12:55.410 --> 01:12:57.540
given that we know
how fast, let's say,

01:12:57.540 --> 01:12:59.830
the American bank
balance would grow,

01:12:59.830 --> 01:13:01.940
we want to know how
fast the British bank

01:13:01.940 --> 01:13:03.380
balance would grow.

01:13:03.380 --> 01:13:07.130
And what affects the growth
rate of the British bank balance

01:13:07.130 --> 01:13:09.770
is the covariance,
actually, between

01:13:09.770 --> 01:13:15.450
the dollar/pound
exchange rate and IBM.

01:13:15.450 --> 01:13:17.510
So remember, we're
investing in IBM

01:13:17.510 --> 01:13:20.030
and we're putting gains
in either an American bank

01:13:20.030 --> 01:13:22.340
or a British bank.

01:13:22.340 --> 01:13:24.550
So IBM stock prices in dollars.

01:13:24.550 --> 01:13:28.110
And so there's no issues
with putting IBM's gains

01:13:28.110 --> 01:13:30.400
in an American bank.

01:13:30.400 --> 01:13:31.960
But there's actually
a subtle effect

01:13:31.960 --> 01:13:35.490
that happens when you put IBM's
gains in a British bank, which

01:13:35.490 --> 01:13:37.830
the subtle effect is there's
this random exchange rate

01:13:37.830 --> 01:13:39.240
dollars per pound.

01:13:39.240 --> 01:13:43.730
And suppose that there's some
correlation, for whatever

01:13:43.730 --> 01:13:49.440
reason, between dollars
per pound and IBM.

01:13:49.440 --> 01:13:52.450
So suppose the correlation's
the following form--

01:13:52.450 --> 01:13:54.780
every time IBM
goes up, the dollar

01:13:54.780 --> 01:13:57.540
gets weaker against the pound.

01:13:57.540 --> 01:14:01.800
So in other words, what happens
is IBM goes up, you go hooray,

01:14:01.800 --> 01:14:02.910
I'm rich.

01:14:02.910 --> 01:14:04.370
I got all these dollars.

01:14:04.370 --> 01:14:07.660
I'm going to go put them
in a British bank account.

01:14:11.390 --> 01:14:16.280
But suppose, unluckily for
you, every time IBM goes up,

01:14:16.280 --> 01:14:18.180
the dollar weakens
against the pound.

01:14:18.180 --> 01:14:25.500
And so, you cannot buy so
many pounds as a result.

01:14:25.500 --> 01:14:28.780
So contrast that with the
opposite situation where

01:14:28.780 --> 01:14:31.170
when IBM goes up, the dollar
strengthens as opposed

01:14:31.170 --> 01:14:32.310
to weakens.

01:14:32.310 --> 01:14:35.220
Then you can buy lots and lots
of pounds with your IBM gains.

01:14:37.820 --> 01:14:40.600
So the correlation between
the dollar pound exchange

01:14:40.600 --> 01:14:44.510
rate and IBM affects how
fast your British bank

01:14:44.510 --> 01:14:45.980
balance would grow.

01:14:45.980 --> 01:14:48.950
And that's actually
like the key point.

01:14:57.440 --> 01:14:59.840
So this would be
well-known to anybody--

01:14:59.840 --> 01:15:01.090
especially an FX client.

01:15:05.210 --> 01:15:12.000
So what we're
actually going to do

01:15:12.000 --> 01:15:16.550
is find a numeraire
such that the growth

01:15:16.550 --> 01:15:21.080
rate of the balance
in that numeraire

01:15:21.080 --> 01:15:26.030
is actually the real-world
drift of the underlying.

01:15:26.030 --> 01:15:30.200
So the idea is let's
say that I told you

01:15:30.200 --> 01:15:32.660
at the beginning of this
talk that historically stocks

01:15:32.660 --> 01:15:34.340
grow at 9% on average.

01:15:38.560 --> 01:15:40.900
Our starting point here
in this part of the talk

01:15:40.900 --> 01:15:45.680
is that we're starting from this
risk-neutral measure Q, which,

01:15:45.680 --> 01:15:49.220
by definition, is the property
that stocks would grow only

01:15:49.220 --> 01:15:49.720
at 1%.

01:15:52.680 --> 01:15:54.390
So what we're
actually going to do

01:15:54.390 --> 01:16:00.980
is go find some numeraire
which will be correlated

01:16:00.980 --> 01:16:08.890
with the stocks, such
that when we put our stock

01:16:08.890 --> 01:16:13.590
gains in that numeraire,
we end up growing at 9%,

01:16:13.590 --> 01:16:14.215
rather than 1%.

01:16:20.080 --> 01:16:25.060
That's the way we
think about things.

01:16:25.060 --> 01:16:28.136
And the key is to find
that numeraire that

01:16:28.136 --> 01:16:28.885
has that property.

01:16:31.940 --> 01:16:33.450
I'm going to go
fast now-- there's

01:16:33.450 --> 01:16:40.130
a paper by John Long where he
shows that that numeraire that

01:16:40.130 --> 01:16:45.130
converts a risk-free growth rate
into the real-world growth rate

01:16:45.130 --> 01:16:46.390
always exists.

01:16:46.390 --> 01:16:48.890
And he gave it a name, and he
called it numeraire portfolio.

01:16:48.890 --> 01:16:51.250
It has another name--
growth optimal portfolio--

01:16:51.250 --> 01:16:52.670
that Kelly was talking about.

01:17:03.670 --> 01:17:06.670
So there's a reference if you're
interested in following up

01:17:06.670 --> 01:17:09.280
on this material.

01:17:12.320 --> 01:17:17.434
So the theory says
that there always

01:17:17.434 --> 01:17:19.100
exists this numeraire
called John Long's

01:17:19.100 --> 01:17:21.170
numeraire portfolio,
such that if you park

01:17:21.170 --> 01:17:25.530
your gains in this
numeraire, you end up growing

01:17:25.530 --> 01:17:27.210
at the real-world drift.

01:17:27.210 --> 01:17:31.180
And so, let's say
all we got to do

01:17:31.180 --> 01:17:35.460
to find that real-world drift is
go find this special numeraire.

01:17:39.310 --> 01:17:43.140
So this part of the talk is
about making some assumptions

01:17:43.140 --> 01:17:48.340
that lead to an identification
of that particular numeraire--

01:17:48.340 --> 01:17:49.260
John Long's numeraire.

01:17:54.680 --> 01:17:57.180
We're going to continue
to work with diffusions.

01:17:57.180 --> 01:18:03.090
And now we're going to also
impose time homogeneity

01:18:03.090 --> 01:18:04.610
like Ross was doing.

01:18:04.610 --> 01:18:07.500
So let's say when I was just
talking about numeraire,

01:18:07.500 --> 01:18:09.400
I was allowing
time inhomogeneity.

01:18:09.400 --> 01:18:12.160
But now we're going to
go time homogeneous.

01:18:14.472 --> 01:18:16.430
I haven't really been
introducing the notation,

01:18:16.430 --> 01:18:19.760
but a(x, t) is the diffusion
coefficient of the state

01:18:19.760 --> 01:18:20.940
variable x.

01:18:20.940 --> 01:18:24.330
And now it's just being assumed
to be a function of x only.

01:18:24.330 --> 01:18:27.180
So b^Q(x, t) was the
drift coefficient of x.

01:18:27.180 --> 01:18:29.570
And now it's a
function of x only.

01:18:29.570 --> 01:18:32.820
r(x, t) was the function
linking the short interest rate

01:18:32.820 --> 01:18:34.030
to the state variable x.

01:18:34.030 --> 01:18:36.310
And now, it's a
function of x only.

01:18:36.310 --> 01:18:40.025
And finally, sigma_L(x, t)
was the volatility of John

01:18:40.025 --> 01:18:41.195
Long's numeraire portfolio.

01:18:41.195 --> 01:18:42.820
And again, that's a
function of x only.

01:18:45.640 --> 01:18:48.330
So anyway, another
assumption that we're

01:18:48.330 --> 01:18:51.110
going to impose now in order
to determine uniquely what

01:18:51.110 --> 01:18:53.460
this numeraire
portfolio value is

01:18:53.460 --> 01:18:57.850
is to require that the diffusion
that's driving everything

01:18:57.850 --> 01:18:59.510
live in a bounded interval.

01:18:59.510 --> 01:19:04.140
So essentially, the
sample paths all

01:19:04.140 --> 01:19:07.600
have to be bounded below
by some constant, which

01:19:07.600 --> 01:19:09.240
could be negative,
and have to be

01:19:09.240 --> 01:19:12.170
bounded above by some constant,
which again could be negative.

01:19:17.800 --> 01:19:20.010
We make all those
assumptions, and we move on.

01:19:20.010 --> 01:19:23.140
And so in the end, what
have we been assuming?

01:19:23.140 --> 01:19:27.029
So we're assuming that there's a
single source of uncertainty X.

01:19:27.029 --> 01:19:28.820
And that it's a
time-homogeneous diffusion.

01:19:28.820 --> 01:19:30.950
So that's this
middle equation here.

01:19:30.950 --> 01:19:34.790
And so that says changes in
X have a predictable part,

01:19:34.790 --> 01:19:36.680
which is b^Q(X) dt.

01:19:36.680 --> 01:19:40.300
And they have an unpredictable
part, which is a of X dW.

01:19:40.300 --> 01:19:43.530
So W there is standard
Brownian motion.

01:19:43.530 --> 01:19:46.950
And since I'm big
on mnemonics, you

01:19:46.950 --> 01:19:49.950
might ask why does W stand
for standard Brownian motion?

01:19:49.950 --> 01:19:52.080
And that's because
W actually stands

01:19:52.080 --> 01:19:54.572
for Wiener process--
Norbert Wiener being an MIT

01:19:54.572 --> 01:19:55.155
mathematician.

01:20:00.430 --> 01:20:03.920
And the W is a standard
notation for this kind of thing.

01:20:07.920 --> 01:20:11.360
As an aside, when Bob Merton was
here working out all this stuff

01:20:11.360 --> 01:20:14.190
for the first time
in the late '60s,

01:20:14.190 --> 01:20:16.650
he knew the standard notation
for standard Brownian motion

01:20:16.650 --> 01:20:18.920
was W. But it turns
out in finance,

01:20:18.920 --> 01:20:22.380
the standard notation
for wealth is also W.

01:20:22.380 --> 01:20:25.460
And he wanted to work on
stochastic wealth dynamics.

01:20:25.460 --> 01:20:28.200
And so he had to choose should
I use the letter W for wealth,

01:20:28.200 --> 01:20:30.790
or should I use the letter
W for Wiener process?

01:20:30.790 --> 01:20:33.090
And he chose W for
wealth, which meant

01:20:33.090 --> 01:20:35.730
he had to pick a different
letter for Wiener process.

01:20:35.730 --> 01:20:40.000
And so he actually
chose the letter Z.

01:20:40.000 --> 01:20:42.017
And you'll have to
ask him why he chose

01:20:42.017 --> 01:20:44.600
that letter, because it doesn't
stand for anything as far as I

01:20:44.600 --> 01:20:48.290
know, except that actually
the sample paths of a Wiener

01:20:48.290 --> 01:20:51.770
process look very jagged,
so if you turn your head,

01:20:51.770 --> 01:20:59.570
you might be able to see a Z.

01:20:59.570 --> 01:21:01.860
So another assumption
is that we're

01:21:01.860 --> 01:21:04.590
going to restrict the possible
dynamics of the numeraire

01:21:04.590 --> 01:21:06.140
portfolio's value.

01:21:06.140 --> 01:21:08.910
So we're going to let
L denote the value

01:21:08.910 --> 01:21:10.140
of this numeraire portfolio.

01:21:10.140 --> 01:21:13.910
And the mnemonic here
is that John Long

01:21:13.910 --> 01:21:17.030
invented this concept, so
we're calling it L for Long.

01:21:17.030 --> 01:21:19.380
Now it's unfortunate that
the inventor of this concept

01:21:19.380 --> 01:21:20.540
was named Long, actually.

01:21:20.540 --> 01:21:24.310
Because in finance, the
word "long" indicates

01:21:24.310 --> 01:21:30.935
that for a security with
a non-negative payoff,

01:21:30.935 --> 01:21:32.310
if you're long,
then you're going

01:21:32.310 --> 01:21:33.604
to be receiving that payoff.

01:21:33.604 --> 01:21:36.020
As you pay money now, you're
going to receive that payoff.

01:21:36.020 --> 01:21:37.650
It's the opposite
of short, where

01:21:37.650 --> 01:21:40.750
if you're short a security
with a non-negative payoff,

01:21:40.750 --> 01:21:43.060
then actually you get
money now and you have

01:21:43.060 --> 01:21:47.000
to deliver that payoff later.

01:21:47.000 --> 01:21:51.620
So as it happens, this
numeraire portfolio

01:21:51.620 --> 01:21:54.010
has multiple positions in it.

01:21:54.010 --> 01:21:55.510
And the signs of
the positions are

01:21:55.510 --> 01:21:59.190
allowed to be real-- so
positives and negatives.

01:21:59.190 --> 01:22:02.140
So it's kind of a misnomer.

01:22:02.140 --> 01:22:03.592
I say Long's
numeraire portfolio,

01:22:03.592 --> 01:22:05.300
and everyone thinks
the positions in them

01:22:05.300 --> 01:22:06.136
are all positive.

01:22:06.136 --> 01:22:07.760
It's not true-- so
they're real-valued.

01:22:12.160 --> 01:22:15.810
The kind of problem
here is that we've

01:22:15.810 --> 01:22:18.460
put the structure on
the value L, John Long's

01:22:18.460 --> 01:22:32.690
numeraire portfolio, namely
that L is a continuous process,

01:22:32.690 --> 01:22:37.452
but it's not quite a
diffusion in itself.

01:22:37.452 --> 01:22:41.550
The only thing you can say
is that the pair X and L

01:22:41.550 --> 01:22:44.179
are a bivariate diffusion.

01:22:44.179 --> 01:22:45.720
If you bring this
L over to the side,

01:22:45.720 --> 01:22:50.160
you can see the coefficients
for dL depend on L and X--

01:22:50.160 --> 01:22:53.230
and same thing with
the volatility part.

01:22:53.230 --> 01:22:56.770
So anyway, we place
the structure.

01:22:56.770 --> 01:23:02.290
And the idea is that we know,
from looking at Bloomberg,

01:23:02.290 --> 01:23:06.950
what the risk-neutral drift
of X is-- that's b^Q(X).

01:23:06.950 --> 01:23:08.160
We know that function.

01:23:08.160 --> 01:23:10.150
We know what the diffusion
coefficient of X is.

01:23:10.150 --> 01:23:11.830
That's the function A of X.

01:23:11.830 --> 01:23:14.250
We know what the
risk-neutral drift of L

01:23:14.250 --> 01:23:16.820
is-- that's that
function r of X.

01:23:16.820 --> 01:23:20.387
But we don't know the
volatility of John Long's

01:23:20.387 --> 01:23:21.220
numeraire portfolio.

01:23:21.220 --> 01:23:23.540
That's the function
sigma_L of X.

01:23:23.540 --> 01:23:27.740
And if only we could find
it, we would actually

01:23:27.740 --> 01:23:32.520
know how to determine
the real-world drift.

01:23:32.520 --> 01:23:38.810
And remember I was saying
if IBM and you could

01:23:38.810 --> 01:23:43.320
put an American bank
account, and let's say there

01:23:43.320 --> 01:23:44.660
was certain growth rate there.

01:23:44.660 --> 01:23:46.660
And then if instead you
were putting those gains

01:23:46.660 --> 01:23:49.320
in a British bank account,
you'd achieve a different growth

01:23:49.320 --> 01:23:50.220
rate.

01:23:50.220 --> 01:23:58.070
And I was stressing that the
correlation of dollar/pound

01:23:58.070 --> 01:24:01.310
with IBM was important for
determining that growth rate.

01:24:01.310 --> 01:24:03.370
And I stand by that.

01:24:03.370 --> 01:24:05.070
When you're in a
one-factor world,

01:24:05.070 --> 01:24:07.280
that correlation
can only be one.

01:24:07.280 --> 01:24:09.290
And so that's what's
happening here.

01:24:09.290 --> 01:24:12.500
We're in a one-factor world,
and that correlation is one.

01:24:12.500 --> 01:24:18.550
And the other thing that
affects the growth rate, though,

01:24:18.550 --> 01:24:21.340
of your British
bank account balance

01:24:21.340 --> 01:24:23.710
is actually the volatility
of the exchange rate.

01:24:23.710 --> 01:24:27.060
So what actually matters
is the covariance

01:24:27.060 --> 01:24:30.940
between the British
exchange rate and IBM.

01:24:30.940 --> 01:24:33.260
That covariance depends
on both the correlation

01:24:33.260 --> 01:24:39.415
and the volatility
of the FX rate.

01:24:39.415 --> 01:24:41.540
So you can think of the FX
rate as here John Long's

01:24:41.540 --> 01:24:42.820
numeraire portfolio.

01:24:42.820 --> 01:24:46.546
And so that sigma_L
is sort of the key.

01:24:46.546 --> 01:24:48.920
It's like we've set things up
so we know the correlation,

01:24:48.920 --> 01:24:51.840
but we still don't
know the covariance.

01:24:51.840 --> 01:24:53.340
And that's what's
actually relevant.

01:24:53.340 --> 01:24:54.940
So as soon as we
get the sigma_L,

01:24:54.940 --> 01:24:56.023
we'll know the covariance.

01:24:58.100 --> 01:24:59.000
So we'll be in shape.

01:25:01.550 --> 01:25:05.279
So we got to find that
volatility function sigma_L.

01:25:05.279 --> 01:25:06.945
And now I know many
of you have classes,

01:25:06.945 --> 01:25:08.790
so I'm going to have
to start moving.

