PETER CARR: Yes,
well actually, you'll

01:25:18.060 --> 01:25:20.185
be glad to know that five
of those are disclaimers.

01:25:23.800 --> 01:25:24.970
If I could move along--

01:25:24.970 --> 01:25:27.020
AUDIENCE: But the
point is to what--

01:25:27.020 --> 01:25:28.870
PETER CARR: The key
is towards the end.

01:25:28.870 --> 01:25:30.100
Yes, absolutely.

01:25:30.100 --> 01:25:30.810
We're very close.

01:25:30.810 --> 01:25:31.310
OK.

01:25:31.310 --> 01:25:34.160
So I'll be done in two minutes.

01:25:34.160 --> 01:25:36.155
So basically,
where we are now is

01:25:36.155 --> 01:25:37.780
we're going to make
one more assumption

01:25:37.780 --> 01:25:39.821
that the value of John
Long's numeraire portfolio

01:25:39.821 --> 01:25:41.929
is a function of X and
D. OK then, let's say

01:25:41.929 --> 01:25:43.220
we've made all our assumptions.

01:25:43.220 --> 01:25:46.310
And where it goes is
that the assumptions

01:25:46.310 --> 01:25:49.310
imply that this
value function splits

01:25:49.310 --> 01:25:51.300
into an unknown
positive function of x,

01:25:51.300 --> 01:25:53.500
and an unknown positive
function of time.

01:25:53.500 --> 01:25:56.990
And when you kind
of further analyze,

01:25:56.990 --> 01:26:00.150
you find that the
unknown function of time

01:26:00.150 --> 01:26:02.000
is an exponential
function of time.

01:26:02.000 --> 01:26:06.050
And the unknown function of x
solves an ordinary differential

01:26:06.050 --> 01:26:11.000
equation of this kind.

01:26:11.000 --> 01:26:13.510
So this is called a
Sturm-Liouville problem.

01:26:13.510 --> 01:26:16.415
And it turns out that
Sturm and Liouville

01:26:16.415 --> 01:26:18.915
were the only mathematicians
I've mentioned in this talk who

01:26:18.915 --> 01:26:20.150
were not at MIT.

01:26:20.150 --> 01:26:24.300
And they actually
solved this problem.

01:26:24.300 --> 01:26:27.400
And one of the
things they show is

01:26:27.400 --> 01:26:31.170
that when you're searching
for functions pi and scalars

01:26:31.170 --> 01:26:34.320
lambda that solve
this problem, there's

01:26:34.320 --> 01:26:40.580
only one solution that delivers
you a positive function pi.

01:26:40.580 --> 01:26:42.240
And so this is how
you get uniqueness.

01:26:45.410 --> 01:26:47.690
Remember I was
saying back with 11--

01:26:47.690 --> 01:26:50.680
so we're searching for like
a 10-vector and a scalar.

01:26:50.680 --> 01:26:52.340
Now the 10 vector is a function.

01:26:52.340 --> 01:26:56.320
And that function is pi,
and the scalar's lambda.

01:26:56.320 --> 01:26:58.072
So the point is is
that the math implies

01:26:58.072 --> 01:26:59.780
there's a unique
solution to the problem.

01:26:59.780 --> 01:27:02.640
So we learn the volatility
of the numeraire portfolio

01:27:02.640 --> 01:27:03.240
in the end.

01:27:03.240 --> 01:27:05.690
And then we learn the
drifts of everything

01:27:05.690 --> 01:27:08.280
you want to know under
the market's beliefs.

01:27:08.280 --> 01:27:11.230
So that's the gist of it.

01:27:11.230 --> 01:27:13.720
So then there's been
work on trying to extend

01:27:13.720 --> 01:27:16.210
to unbounded intervals.

01:27:16.210 --> 01:27:19.750
And basically, in the
famous Black-Scholes model,

01:27:19.750 --> 01:27:24.010
this effort fails, whereas
in the less famous but still

01:27:24.010 --> 01:27:28.000
important Cox-Ingersoll-Ross
model, this effort succeeds.

01:27:28.000 --> 01:27:31.270
So the sort of
punchline is that when

01:27:31.270 --> 01:27:36.040
it comes to unbounded state
space, the theory's open.

01:27:36.040 --> 01:27:38.090
So if there's a grad
student in the room who

01:27:38.090 --> 01:27:40.660
wants a good dissertation
problem, this is it.

01:27:40.660 --> 01:27:41.160
OK.

01:27:41.160 --> 01:27:43.410
So that's all I
wanted to say today.

01:27:43.410 --> 01:27:44.960
